2) Special Summon these Gravekeeper monsters with Saryuja and "Monster Reborn". When Cannonholder is around, tribute Curse to deal damage and revive Curse back with "Monster Reborn".

3) Repeat what was explained in #2 until your opponent is dead.

deck_excerpt: Hiro Mill OTK ft. Morphing Jar #2+Wattfox+Wanghu
deck_description:
Greetings! In this deck, we will mill the opponent with "Hiro's Shadow Scout" alongside series of combinations to not get interrupted by any means. Let's have a look.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Link Summon Saryuja when you have 4 cards in your Main Deck (MD) and shuffle back 3, all of which has to be spells. Then, Special Summon Hiro with Saryuja but only if you have up to 3 x MD monsters, including Hiro. Also, although not mandatory, place Baronne on Main Monster Zone (MMZ).

2) Clear at least 2 x MMZ with Ravenous/Baronne/Raigeki. Then, set all Traps and end your turn. During your opponent's Draw Phase, activate these Traps in order explained below:

  1. Powerful Rebirth >>> Wattfox
  2. Reverse Reuse >>> MJ #2 as face-down
  3. Give and Take >>> Wanghu
  4. All-Out Attacks

3) What is going to happen is that Wanghu destroys Wattfox, which shuts down anything your opponent can try to break you, including hand-traps. Then, via All-Out Attacks, MJ #2 will flip face-up and you can start milling your opponent. While your Traps are resolving, feel free to negate one thing your opponent can activate in response to them with Baronne.

4) After your job is done with Traps, MJ #2 is going to excavate three monsters, which are MJ #2 + Hiro + Wanghu. Should it come to that, place these monsters in order below and know that if you have two more Main Deck monsters, place them as last:

  1. MJ #2
  2. Hiro
  3. Wanghu

5) Now, your opponent draws 3 cards each time Hiro has been activated. So, repeat what was explained in #4 until your opponent is out of cards.

deck_excerpt: Be the reason someone quits master duel.
deck_description:
I want you to be aware that this deck is the problem. It is a condensed ball of every problem Yugioh boomers and other card game players will lie about on Twitter. Usually, this is just nonsense, but in our case, it is a guide. Run down the timer with your combos, throw out stupid staples, and make a million negates.

Be the reason someone quits master duel.

 

So here’s my modern-day deck list for 60 6 samurai. It’s very straightforward, you’re playing 3 of every six samurai monster that can spam out other six samurai monsters or special summon themselves for free. 3 Kizaru, 3 Grandmaster, 3 Great Shogun Shien, and 3 Kageki.

We’re also running 3 Mizuho and 3 Shinai. Each one of these special summons themself from their hand if you control the other. This matters since they’re searchable from secret Six Samurai Kizaru. Even more so since this deck’s best 2 extenders are rank 3.

This gets us into a larger point of strategy. Counter generation. Six Samurai as a deck revolve around generating bushido counters every time a Six Samurai monster is summoned. Gateway of the Six Samurai let’s us search for a Six Samurai monster for every 4 counters anywhere. But it only generates 2 counters for each summon. This means we either need multiple counter-generating cards or we can use extenders to turn every 2 monsters into a different 2 monsters and some counters.

For example. 2 levels 3’s go into M-X Saber invoker which goes into kizaru and a search. Or islolde into hatsune. Going two for 2.5 lets the deck deal with heavy costs and negs that come with link spamming and starting combos.

I’ll also mention here the three great shogun shien. It’s a hard floodgate of an opponent’s spells and traps that summons itself for free. In the TCG I’d be a bit more hesitant about running it, but in Master Duel's janky best-of-one format it’s so much stronger than it has any right to be.

This list makes use of several powerful engines. Most notable is the Kashtira engine. It’s a simple tool that gets us disruption removal and free attack thanks to the field spell.

But even more interesting is the zodiac engine. Zodiac Barrage has no restrictions or real cost so At its most basic it pulls out an extra material for a link monster or just an extra disruption with Zoodiac Drident. But more interestingly we can use zodiac barrage to destroy six samurai fuma to trigger her effect.  So it ends up being a plus one. Fuma is also searchable thanks to Isolde two tales of the noble knights or literally any six samurai searcher.

Zodiac Barrage and Kashtiras contribute to what put this deck head and shoulders above my early iterations. Not only is it a stupid wombo combo deck, but you have tools to play going second.

 

The extra deck is very straightforward. Let’s split it into extenders and end board.

We have the before-mentioned extenders of mx saber invoker and Isolde but let me explain the other 3. Battle Shogun of the Six Samurai is a searcher for Gateway of the Six Samurai. He does take as discard and doesn’t lead to any further plays on his own so he has to be used either in specific 3-4 card combos or after we’ve done some setup with Isolde and M-X Saber Invoker. Basically, unless you're guaranteed to have follow up don’t make him.

Skull Dread Saryuja is a bread and butter extender. Especially since most of this deck is extenders and 1-card engines. Drawing 4 is crazy and with some extra searches, thanks to Isolde, Gateway and Kizaru the put-back 3 cost doesn’t hurt.

Leviar is an extender’s extender. If we have already used mx saber invoker and Isolde to make Hatsume we can then follow up the hatsume skill with a leviair. To keep the loops going. It’s very overkill, but does sustain some otherwise suboptimal starts.

For our end boards, we have a large chunk dedicated to generic link spam. IP Masquerna lets us benefit from leaving out materials. Knightmare Gryphon is a monster effect negate floodgate. Appollosa is just 4 monster negates. And Underworld Goddess is a out to problematic monsters and an extra target for I:P.

For XYZ’s we have Abyss Dweller and Bagooska. Bagooska is a simple backup plan. Abyss Dweller is an anti-graveyard floodgate. Master Duel being a best-of-one format makes this awkward to use. Since you kinda just gotta feel it.

Naturia Beast and six samurai shien are our spell negates. Of course, Naturia Beast is a much better play but we need access to Shien’s Squire to get it. This means we have to go through a limited number of good but not guaranteed options to get it from the deck. Much more often we’ll go for shi en who’s only 1 spell or trap negate.

Uh oh, Number 43 is on the rampage and it's willing to smash everything with its new tank.

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, send Number 13 to GY and bring forth Smashtank.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup a "Primal Seed" loop. Just don't banish Number 13 by accident and you will be fine.

3) Revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into Number 43 with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch".

4) Fetch all cards from Banish Zone (BZ) to your hand with "Primal Seed" and activate Smashtank to discard all but "Mystik Wok" to boost its ATK.

5) With Smashtank having huge amount of ATK points, activate "Mystik Wok" to target Smashtank and choose its ATK. The amount you gained as LP can be reflected as damage to your opponent thanks to Number 43.

6) Congratulations, you win the game!

deck_excerpt: cute n smol runick-powered melffys + tri-brigade support
deck_description:
Melffys are cute as fuck but dead serious when it comes to be a major annoyance for your opponent.

Runick Fountain and Melffy Hide-and-Seek makes for a great drawing / recycling engine.

Hugin the Runick Wings searches for Runick Fountain and can be used as a rk.2 xyz or synchro material.

The Runick engine combined with the melffy engine allows you to respond to each of your opponent's actionduring their turn. Melffy Wally can bring Melffy Catty and Melffy Puppy out. Then they can bring Melffy Pinny or Hop Ear Squadron to your hand and summon a beast to your field like Tri-Brigade Kitt, which can lead to the synchro summon of Merry Melffys or Desert Locusts, which can itself be used to summon Borreload Dragon or Baronne de Fleur, all of that during your opponent's turn! Melffy of the Forest and each of your Runick spells can further block your opponent and destroy their cards.

Tri-Brigade Shuraig the Ominous Omen works wonderfully with the melffy engine, allowing you to banish a card on the field (without targetting) each single turn as you summon out your smol creatures. Rescue Cat summons out Tri-Brigade Kitt and Melffy Pinny (or any other lv 2 beast), which can be used to summon Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom. Tri-Brigade Kitt sends Tri-Brigade Nervall to the grave, which adds Tri-Brigade Kerass to your hand. Summon the bad boy, get another link2 monster out and then Shuraig can come out.

In a nutshell: this deck can go crazy! Try it!

Placement: 2nd Place

It's times like these when I realize how much I am blinded by the presence of World Legacy Monstrosity at times. Today's Level 9 monster we are taking a look at is Deskbot 009 which is a Level 9 EARTH Machine monster whereas its effect could matter less. I should've come to realization of what a Deskbot Prediction Princess Deck should be much sooner, but at the time, I was thinking "Deskbot 009 is an EARTH monster, this is not going to work," like a dumbdumb and I completely forgot that Machine Duplication exists. You see, every Deskbot monster has 500 ATK/DEF and they each have their own ways of increasing their ATK/DEF to very large amounts. They are practically begging you to use Machine Duplication with them. And the Deskbot cards actually make getting to 009 extremely easy, specifically Deskbot 003 does. On Normal Summon, 003 can Special Summon a Deskbot monster from Deck, except for itself, which can immediately get a 009 onto the field. There you go. End of story. Now just activate Machine Duplication for 2 more copies of 009 from Deck, and now you've got yourself Rank 9 access and an additional Level 9 monster to boot. So all you really need for combo is Deskbot 003 and Machine Duplication. Now, we are playing Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag and 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which we can use for Bibliomuse access through Summoning Kaku for free (by Linking 003 into Salamangreat Almiraj), but we don't exactly need to rely on it. And if we don't draw Monstrosity or Machine Dupe, we can just use 009 and Kaku as Rank 9 access. You could instead play a Pre-Preparation of Rites package with Prediction Ritual but I like Bibliomuse access more. 

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. For our Flips, we have 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck. 3 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag which can Special Summoned from hand if there is a monster in the Extra Monster Zone. This is extremely easy to do in this Deck with you being able to Link off a Normal Summoned Diviner of the Herald or Deskbot 003 for a Salamangreat Almiraj. Also, you can target a face-up monster in the EMZ and equip it and when this card destroys a monster by battle, you can Special Summon a monster card that is equipped to it. Kaku is good for just getting a Level 9 onto the field, but it can also act as removal in some applications as well. And on top of both of those things, it makes for a good Small World bridge due to its Type and Attribute. 3 Deskbot 009 and 3 Deskbot 003. 009 is just a Level 9 monster that we can easily access through 003 and Machine Dupe. 003 can Special Summon a Deskbot straight from Deck on Normal Summon. Both have 500 ATK which means that they can both be targeted by Machine Duplication and because Machine Dupe is not a once per turn, if you draw more than one, you can dupe 009 first for Rank 9 plays and then dupe 003 for Link plays. 3 Diviner of the Herald which sends a Fairy from Deck or Extra Deck to GY to increase its Level by the Level of the sent monster. And because it has 500 ATK and is a LIGHT Fairy, it makes as a good way to bridge to 003. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. 

Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can also banish it from GY during the Standby Phase in order to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 3 Small World. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from Deck with a different Type and Attribute than it but with different names. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Machine Duplication which targets a Machine monster you control with 500 or less ATK and Special Summons up to 2 monsters from Deck with the same name as that monster. And finally, 3 Pot of Prosperity. 

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which sends a monster from Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon and can target monsters in your GY up to the number of its materials, detach the same number of materials, and attach those monsters in GY to itself as material. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Underworld. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Gravity Controller and 1 Salamangreat Almiraj. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 1 Kurikara Divincarnate, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Infinite Impermanence, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: So Isolde got banned, now what? Let's do this.
deck_description:
Intro

Isolde got banned in the most recent Forbidden/Limited list so this deck got a massive hit. All warrior extenders are not useful now because in order to do the same combo as before we now need 2 Goukis instead of 2 Warriors. So let's look at the current combos:

Combos

[Combo #1]: 1 Suprex + 1 other Gouki (not Headbatt)

  1. Normal Summon Gouki Suprex > effect to Special Summon other Gouki (ex. Gouki Twistcobra)
  2. Link Summon Gouki Jet Ogre > Goukis' effects in GY to add Gouki Headbatt and another Gouki (ex. Gouki Riscorpio)
  3. Headbatt effect to Special Summon it discarting Riscorpio.
  4. Link Summon Gouki Thunder Ogre > Headbatt effect to add another Gouki (ex. Gouki Iron Claw)
  5. Extra Normal Summon Iron Claw.
  6. Link Summon Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess > Iron Claw effect to add Gouki Re-Match.
  7. Activate Re-Match special summoning Riscorpio and another Gouki.
  8. Link Summon Codebreaker Virus Swordsman > effect to Special Summon Codebreaker Zero Day and Riscorpio effect to add Re-Match.
  9. Link Summon Codebreaker Virus Berserker > effect to Special Summon back the Virus Swordsman and Zero Day.
  10. Link Summon them into The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche to the right zone.
  11. Bardiche effect sending The Phantom Knights of Silent Boots to GY and setting The Phantom Knights of Shade Brigandine.
  12. Activate Brigandine summoning itself as a monster.
  13. Link Summon Gouki The Powerload Ogre with Berserker and Brigandine.
  14. Silent Boots effect in GY banishing itself to add Phantom Knights' Fog Blade, set it and End Turn.

End Board: 3 monster negates (2 from Apollousa and 1 from Fog Blade) and 1 unaffected monster (Powerload)

Note: In step 11 you can set 1 other Fog Blade instead of the Brigandine to end with 4 monster negates.

[Combo #2]: 1 Headbatt + 2 other different Goukis

  1. Normal Summon a Gouki (ex. Riscorpio)
  2. Headbatt effect to Special Summon it discarting another Gouki (ex. Twistcobra)
  3. Link Summon Jet Ogre > Goukis' effects in GY to add Re-Match and Suprex.
  4. Activate Re-Match special summoning Twistcobra and another Gouki.
  5. Link Summon Thunder Ogre using Jet Ogre and Twistcobra > Twistcobra effect to add another Gouki (ex. Iron Claw)
  6. Extra Normal Summon Suprex > effect to Special Summon Iron Claw.
  7. Link Summon Apollousa using Thunder Ogre and Iron Claw > Iron Claw effect to add Re-Match.
  8. [Continue with step 8 from Combo #1]

[Combo #3]: Going Second OTK

  1. Normal Summon Suprex > effect to Special Summon Twistcobra.
  2. Link Summon Jet Ogre > Goukis' effects in GY to add Headbatt and another Gouki (ex. Riscorpio)
  3. Headbatt effect to Special Summon it discarting Riscorpio.
  4. Link Summon Thunder Ogre > Headbatt effect to add Re-Match.
  5. Activate Re-Match special summoning Riscorpio and Twistcobra.
  6. Link Summon Gouki The Master Ogre > Riscorpio effect to add Gouki Finishing Move.
  7. Activate Finishing Move.
  8. Go to Battle Phase.
  9. Attack with Master Ogre > on Damage Step activate Twistcobra's effect to tribute itself to give more ATK to Master Ogre.

8400 battle damage.

[Combo #4]: Bricking

  1. Set a Gouki and Torrential Tribute.
  2. End Phase.
  3. Add Suprex when the set Gouki gets destroyed.

Yep.

deck_excerpt: I'm holding out for a HERO!
deck_description: Deck is as competative of a deck as I could theorycraft. I'm a huge fan of heroes and this is my attempt to bring my spin on a deck that could stand a chance against these newer decks
Just cyber dragons
Ib the World Chalice Justiciar + World Legacy - "World Chalice" can summon Baronne de Fleur. Auram the World Chalice Blademaster + Link Spider can summon Decode Talker Heatsoul.
Playable witchcrafter deck. May be tier 2 or lower but have a chance to win :)

One-Card Starters:

(9) Herald (Spell Negate) + Laevateinn + Trias in GY + Boss Stage:

3x Wakaushi

3x Bike -> Wakaushi

3x Wagon -> Gigant X -> Wakaushi (Note: Any way to Gigant X is Full-Combo)

(17) Ways to get to Boss Stage:

3x Wakaushi, 3x Bike, 3x Wagon, 3x Loptyr, 1x Planet Pathfinder, 1x Terraforming, 3x Boss Stage

Strengths:

Almost without fail, if left uninterrupted you get to go full combo without a hitch. Typically if you don't full-combo, it's because you already drew what you were searching and just opened boss stage + monstrosity anyways. There are also a lot of two-card combos that get you to the ideal board even if you don’t draw any starters, but in most cases you’re working with one-card combos that use additional cards as extension to play through hand traps.

An issue this deck had previously was drawing a Generaider you wanted to summon off of Boss Stage. No more, Lee allows you to trade any monster in your hand for itself, which turns a brick into a negate so long as Herald of Mirage Lights is on the field. Summon Vala off of Boss Stage, et voila. 

One also might be concerned about mixing Spells with Superheavy, but this deck actually has a good answer for that. When summoning Jormungandr using Laevateinn, you can equip any spells from grave that might dead a Superheavy on a future turn if it looks like you might have to go for a second round of combo.

The Superheavies also give you access to a Pendulum Summon - Regrettably only at a maximum scale of 8, but that’s more than enough to Pend extra superheavies, Lee, or Loptyr. 

Weaknesses & Deck Building Concessions:

There's a really good argument to play 1 Superheavy Samurai Scales and a decent argument to play 1 Superheavy Samurai Security, as they can sometimes help you play through hand traps. That's the main reason Soulgaia Booster and Soulpiercer were bumped to three, and Vala cut to 1. I didn’t feel comfortable including them due to how many garnets this deck already has, but they do have their own merit. I even spent time testing Superheavy Samurai Magnet as a way to increase the amount of two-card combos and as a way to bait/play through interruption, but at least in my testing, it didn’t result in any meaningful/guaranteed additional lines.

I didn't feel good about it, but I cut the Ty-Phon for Baronne & Assault Synchro Stardust Dragon. Cutting Crocodragon Archethys didn't feel bad; Typically if you're able to make it you're already winning anyways. If you get hand trapped once or twice, if you can't force through to Ib & Monstrosity you can usually at least end on Baronne. You might cut Trencher for Ty-Phon, but I’m not familiar enough with Generaider to make that call.

If your opponent holds the Ash for Monstrosity, you're screwed... Unless you can weave in Gigant X for Pathfinder before summoning Trishula, in which case you can just pend it out. You at least still get to Boss Stage in this scenario, and I liked having a secondary way to bridge the Superheavies to the Generaiders. If you open Pathfinder, just think of it as bad Loptyr.

The Ib and Soulpiercer searches are typically chainblocked by Wakaushi effect to scale itself and Tilting effect to summon Wakaushi from the extra respectively.

A hand trap on Titling/Gigant X typically hurts as well, though sometimes it just doesn't matter and you can play through it either by setting up an additional Superheavy body or by using it to bait interaction when you already have another way to Wakaushi. Same goes for an Ash on specifically Big Benkei. However, all of these spots are risky to hand trap since certain extenders let you play through them unscathed; The conundrum is kind of like pre-banlist R-ACE.

I tried really hard to make a version of the combo where you summon Baronne before triggering Monstrosity, but I seriously struggled to make both happen. You’re usually missing a tuner.

I cut the Diviner lines because most of the time, you'd rather have a Special summon as opposed to a 2nd or 3rd normal summon stuck in your hand. It also allows you to cut Nidhogg, since you no longer have to worry about activating Monstrosity on Trias Hierarchia.

Conclusion:

You’re still playing Generaider. You still have the potential to lose to every hand trap under the sun, but at least this build can sometimes play through them. However, the heightened ceiling that the guaranteed access to Monstrosity provides (via Ib) is ludicrous. If you pull off the combo, you’ve pretty much won the game on the spot. I struggle to imagine a deck that can break this board consistently without cards like Lava Golem or Sphere Mode.
I use this deck when I am crazy.

deck_name: Dragon Ruler deck,Ib the World Chalice Justiciar,Snatch Steal, post banlist 2024

deck_excerpt: Deck divertido y potente basado en el arquetipo Mundo Oscuro y ¡Peligro!
deck_description:
Deck ideal para salir de primer turno.

La idea es invocar cuanto antes a Ceruli, Guru of Dark World en el Campo del rival, teniendo a Sillva, Warlord of Dark World en la Mano, para descartar esta segunda carta al Cementerio y activar su efecto, que quita cartas de la Mano del adversario.

Genta, Gateman of Dark World es clave para traer la Mágica de Campo, la cual permite: desterrar, normalmente a Genta, que se invoca de forma especial; descartar, para activar efectos en el Cementerio de nuestros monstruos y robar.

Los monstruos Danger! Bigfoot!, Danger! Thunderbird!, Danger! Chupacabra!, Danger! Mothman!, Danger! Nessie!, Danger!? Tsuchinoko? y Danger!? Jackalope? permiten agilizar el Deck e invocarse a sí mismos de modo especial (robando, además, una carta) o activar sus efectos en el Cementerio para destruir cartas (principalmente). 

Nibiru, the Primal Being y Radian, the Multidimensional Kaiju permiten tributar Monstruos del rival e interrumpirle combos y posiciones de Monstruo en su campo. Pueden ser sustituidos por Lava Golem (en el Side Deck) para, además, infligirle 1000 LP de daño en su Standby Phase.

El Deck Extra posee monstruos con gran ataque y dificiles de matar, como Number 22: Zombiestein. Además, cuenta con el combo Number 97: Draglubion - Number 100: Numeron Dragon y la Fusión de Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World que permite cambiar el efecto de una Mágica, Trampa o Monstruo del rival para descartarnos una carta y seguir moviendo el Deck.

Skill Drain es bastante útil contra Decks que se basan en activar efectos de Monstruos sobre el Campo. ¡OJO! Puede ser activado, solamente, durante la Standby Phase o cuando tu adversario active un efecto de Monstruo sobre el Campo y, además, también te afecta a ti.
spellcaster control 2

This is a simple more pure Dogmatika. It has many starters allowing you to get things going.

Ash can even be used as a starter to link into Almiraj and then Gardna. I love Iblee lock and honestly, it gets me a scoop more often than not, and if not doing the combo to rip more than half of their extra deck gets me the scoop. One huge weakness is people with little or no extra deck usage so I added a branded twist to the deck to balance this allowing for big extra deck monsters to also be summoned. There is also the ability to summon Luluwalilith with using her as either a target with Maximus if you see no way to get Alba Zoa or if you are able to summon Alba Zoa summoning Cartesia at the end of the turn. Use her effect only when your opponent uses a monster effect to summon a monster (Thing Magician Souls or Mathtech) allowing you to summon Grang in the chain, then when the monster is summoned you can use both his effects using the first to send him to the GY then using the 2nd effect to summon Luluwalilith.

While this deck does have flaws and is in no way Meta, you can still climb high and to be honest I use it as I love it. The changes you could make is one less Dogmatikalamity for another thrust or swap Iblee for Maxx c and while it pains me to say this White Relic & White Knight see very veryyyyy little play but are good when you find that perfect slot. If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

So, in total, you can save up to 630 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Natural Disaster FTK ft. The Dark Magicians
deck_description:
Welcome! In this deck, we will FTK with "Natural Disaster" thanks to assistance coming from "The Dark Magicians". Let me explain.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place Librarian on Main Monster Zone (MMZ) and discard Cirrostratus with Ravenous/Dugares.

2) When you have 4 cards in Main Deck, Link Summon Saryuja but don't use Librarian as material. Then, shuffle back all three "Natural Disaster" cards. After placing ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summoning Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup Primal Seed loop, Special Summon Parasite with Saryuja. This enables you to Fusion Summon "The Dark Magicians".

3) Play "The Humble Sentry" to shuffle "Give and Take" and activate Magicians to draw a Trap and set it.

4) Play "De-Fusion" to reset Magicians, which lets you draw rest of your Traps. When you have all Traps ready to go, activate "Give and Take" at first and then all "Natural Disaster" cards at last. If you have done everything right, each time Cirrostratus pops, you will deal 500 x 3 = 1500 damage in total.

5) In order to repeat what was explained in #4, you have to do what was told in #3 to win the game.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "The Dark Magicians" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 30 UR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Baronne de Fleur" can be found within "The Noble Knights of Crimson Flowers" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 180 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

Once again in my never-ending crusade to make my favorite archetypes cook in ways I never thought possible, I have found the best way to play Gameciel Turbo! Now, the concept of this deck is simple, go into Gameciel with Kyoutou Waterfront and bully our opponent with well-timed non one per turn omni-negates. However, because Konami won't give Kaijus any new support (hopefully for now), our best shot of playing Kyoutou are opening it, Terraforming, or Ancient Fairy Dragon and because Kaijus are limited by their own summon clause, Saryuja Skull Dread is our best friend.

 

Now what deck can link climb, synchro summon, AND search Kyoutou? Why Crusadia, of course! With two card combos that can end on two Link 4s, this deck has the sauce to get the job done. And of course, because it's me, I got a nice, little tech that gasses up the deck surprisingly well. The honorary Crusadia monsters Parallel eXceed and Link Infra-Flier are perfect for the deck and searchable with Cynet Mining for the latter, giving the deck functionally 7-8 more Crusadia monsters to extend with (depending on personal ratios), which means tehnically one Crusadia name is full combo with one of those cards.

 

The deck isn't the best, of course. The right number of negates can shut it down and that stupid rock is a thorn in its side, but if it can pop-off, it's a threat to behold. Not to mention it cheap, so you could cook it up for a relatively low price. What Kaijus you use outside of Gameciel (if any at all) is up to you all.

Wightsworn is a great support monster for the Skull Servant archetype. His effects improve the consistency and impact of plays.

Wightbaking Starter Example

1. Normal summon Wightbaking.

2. Link summon Linkuriboh by using Wightbaking as material.

3. Activate Wightbaking's graveyard effect to add Wightsworn and Wightprince to the hand, then discard Wightprince.

4. Activate Wightprince's effect to send Skull Servant and The Lady in Wight to the graveyard.

5. Activate Wightsworn's effect to mill cards from the deck equal to the amount of Skull Servants in the graveyard.

Depending on what was milled, you can potentially revive a Skull Servant or King of the Skull Servants with Wightsworn's graveyard effect! You can also special summon King of the Skull Servants from the deck with Wightprince's effect. Lastly, the Linkuriboh on the board is some good material for summoning S:P Little Knight!

On Mill Support

The Horus engine can summon The Zombie Vampire, which mills the top 4 cards from both player's decks and can revive a monster sent to the graveyard with this effect. Uni-Zombie and Immortal Dragon can send any zombie, such as Mezuki, to the graveyard. Mezuki can revive a zombie with his graveyard effect.

Let's dive in! This deck was crafted purely for the joy of creating a fun experience with normal monsters. The core strategy revolves around establishing a solid defense until you can unleash the powerful 2-card combo: Triangle Power and The Law of Normal. This sets the stage for an ultimate attack, likely turning the tide in your favor and potentially concluding the battle. Success with this deck requires a bit of luck, but the thrill is amplified when facing opponents using cards from the same Yu-Gi-Oh timeline. Get ready for an exciting and suspenseful game!

Get ready to DUEL! Here's an attempt to recreate a potentially Joey Wheeler anime deck. The strategy is to incorporate cards used by Joey in the anime and make the deck as competitive as possible. The focus is on utilizing classic Warrior-type monsters, aiming to swiftly bring them onto the field. The stars of the show are Command Knight and Blue Flame Swordsman, serving as the deck's cornerstone. While these two cards are pivotal, the deck also offers other entertaining moves that can secure a victory. Keep in mind that this deck is designed for fun rather than pure competitiveness, so gather your old friends, assemble the specified cards, and dive into an enjoyable duel!

Let's keep the momentum going! Here, we're exploring the classic dynamics of a Goat Control deck. The game plan is straightforward: two heavyweights, Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning and Thousand-Eyes Restrict, take charge of the battles. The key lies in hand card control, ensuring you have answers to counter your opponent's moves until the opportune moment to unleash these powerhouses. It's a well-constructed deck with competitive characteristics, making it a delight to try out. Enjoy the experience, and always remember, it's time to DUEL!

Oh, get ready for an intriguing discussion! Here it is! We're diving into a Goat Format Exodia-inspired deck with a touch of the Empty Jar strategy. The objective isn't just to summon Exodia but rather to force your opponent's deck to run dry! The powerhouses in this setup are Cyber Jar and Morphing Jar, combined with The Shallow Grave and Book of Taiyou strategically played at the right moments. This concoction allows you to bring your opponent to the brink of exhaustion. While the potential for an Exodia combo is high, the key is to focus on the bigger picture. Look at the forest, and the Exodia pieces will fall into place if you believe in the heart of the cards!

deck_name: Fusion Ancient Gear Prediction Princess Post LEDE
deck_excerpt: Making Ancient Gear Megaton Golem A Reality
deck_description:
Yes, I've seen the banlist, I know that Ib the World Chalice Justiciar is now unbanned, but I don't see it being too much of a boon for Prediction Princess unless you are either playing Runick Prediction Princess or find a consistent way to get 2 other cards in its column to make it a Tuner (which is to go second which is a no-go for Prediction Princess). Either way, the Ancient Gear support from Legacy of Destruction was revealed and I am quite impressed with we got. If anything, it heavily supports the Fusion aspect of the Deck, giving you a much easier way to get an Ancient Gear Golem onto the field, or in this case, Ancient Gear Dark Golem, whose name becomes Ancient Gear Golem on field, while also giving you an easy way to search for Ancient Gear Fusion. And because you have an Ancient Gear Golem on field, you are now able to Fuse using materials from Deck with Ancient Gear Fusion. The Level 9 monster we are looking at today is Ancient Gear Megaton Golem which is a Level 9 EARTH Machine Fusion Monster that requires 3 Ancient Gear Monsters as material. I could care less about what its effect does. However, the Ancient Gear support makes this card comically easy to get out onto the field, and even two of them for that fact. In my previous Ancient Gear Prediction Princess Deck that featured Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon as our Level 9 of choice, I talked about not even trying to make Megaton Golem because of how hard it was for Ancient Gears to get to their Fusion Monsters unless you literally draw the right 3 or 4-card combo. But their support in Legacy of Destruction requires a simple 2.5 card combo. You need Ancient Gear Tanker, Ancient Gear Dark Golem, and a discard. Normal Summon Tanker whose effect triggers on Normal Summon to Special Summon an Ancient Gear from hand ignoring its Summoning Conditions. Special Summon Dark Golem whose effect on Special Summon triggers to add up to 2 Ancient Gear cards and/or Geartown from your Deck to your hand, then discarding a card. Add Ancient Gear Fusion and Geartown. Activate Geartown and then use Tanker's effect to pop it. If you have a second copy of Ancient Gear Fusion in hand, use Geartown's effect to Special Summon another copy of Ancient Gear Dark Golem from Deck. If you don't, then just Special Summon Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon from hand, Deck, or GY. Activate Ancient Gear Fusion to fuse using your Dark Golem on field and 2 other Ancient Gears in Deck to Fusion Summon Ancient Gear Megaton Golem. From here, you can go for a Rank 9, or if you have the second Gear Fusion and Special Summoned another Ancient Gear Dark Golem off of Geartown, you can Fuse into another Megaton Golem if you want. Is this Deck better than the version of Ancient Gear Prediction Princess that focuses on Reactor Dragon? I think that both Decks' consistency is pretty much around the same. You need to jump through more hoops when it comes to Fusion Ancient Gear Prediction Princess compared to normal Ancient Gear Prediction Princess, but the Fusion variant is definitely much cooler and seems almost like an add-on to the previous version, giving you the boon of being able to utilize the Ancient Gear Fusion Monsters like Megaton Golem and Chaos Giant as OTK tools. 

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can also Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during the End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase Effect. Her Flip Effect allows you to Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down, and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of monsters you control either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY if she was tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect allows you to search for a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck and while she is face-up on field, she gives all of your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler and 1 Pot of the Forbidden. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it. Pot of the Forbidden's Flip Effect allows you to choose 1 effect between drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, and looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card of your choice from it back into the Deck. For the Ancient Gear monsters, we are playing 1 Ancient Gear Reactor Dragon, 3 Ancient Gear Dark Golem, and 3 Ancient Gear Tanker. Before I get into them, I want to talk about Ancient Gear Commander. While it is on field, you can send an Ancient Gear Golem from yoru hand, Deck, or face-up Monster Zone to the GY to immediately Normal Summon an Ancient Gear monster. And if you Normal or Special Summon Ancient Gear Golem, you can Special Summon an Ancient Gear Golem from your hand or GY ignoring its Summoning Conditions. And you can also banish Commander from GY to place an Ancient Gear Continuous Trap from your hand face-up on your field. Ancient Gear Commander is not a bad card. If anything, it gives Ancient Gears something to do turn 1 other than make Ancient Gear Howitzer pass. But there are several issues that prevent it from being too good or realistically that good in a non-pure Ancient Gear Deck like this one. For one, you need to play the original Ancient Gear Golem for its effect. Ancient Gear Golem - Ultimate Pound is not listed in its effect which goes against the entirety of the Legendary Duelists Ancient Gear support with cards like Ancient Gear Frame, Ancient Gear Megaton Golem, Ancient Gear Fusion, and Cross-Dimensional Duel mentioning Ultimate Pound in their effect next to the original Ancient Gear Golem. Ultimate Pound does not have its name be treated as Ancient Gear Golem at all, so it would've been really nice if we were able to utilize Ultimate Pound with the Legacy of Destruction Ancient Gear support. Like imagine Special Summoning Ultimate Pound with Tanker and popping it with Tanker's effect to search for a Polymerization and adding back another Ancient Gear from GY to have the ability to go into Guardian Chimera. I'm not saying that you would be playing Ultimate Pound if the support did name it, but it would've been nice to have the option to do so, especially in my case because Guardian Chimera is a Level 9 which is great for Monstrosity purposes. This all makes Ancient Gear Commander better in a pure version of Ancient Gear rather than in a Deck utilizing the Ancient Gear cards as a supplemental engine. Its effects require you to play the original Ancient Gear Golem and the plays that it does manage to facilitate are better for pure Ancient Gears going first. Going back to the Ancient Gears we are playing, Reactor Dragon is a Level 9 that we can access from hand, Deck, or GY by popping our copy of Geartown that we will be searching. You could play 2, but I feel like it is non-ironically better and easier to just fuse into a Megaton Golem for the second Level 9. Ancient Gear Dark Golem is treated as Ancient Gear Golem while on field or in GY. If it is Normal or Special Summoned, you can add up to 2 Ancient Gear cards and/or Geartown from your Deck then discard a card at the cost of being unable to set cards for the rest of the turn. And of course, it has the Ancient Gear effect of making your opponent unable to activate Spell/Trap cards if it attacks until the end of the Damage Step. I want to note that Dark Golem does not say that the cards you search need to be of different names. You can search 2 Ancient Gear Fusion or 2 Geartown if you really wanted which is nice to know based on what hand you draw. Tanker can Special Summon an Ancient Gear from hand other than itself ignoing its Summoning Conditions on Normal or Special Summon. But if your opponent controls a monster, you can Special Summon that monster from your GY instead. While it is on the field, you can target a face-up card you control and destroy it to give all Ancient Gear Golem and all monsters you control that mention it 600 ATK for the rest of the turn. You could play Ultimate Pound to go with Ancient Gear Tanker, but getting Dark Golem off of it is so much better considering that you can search for Geartown off of Dark Golem and pop it with Tanker. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down, and you can also banish it from your GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from your Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which is used to Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can also banish it from your GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 2 Clockwork Night which turns all face-up monsters on the field into Machine monsters, giving all of your Machine monsters 500 ATK/DEf while your opponent's Machine monsters lose 500 ATK/DEF. But the effect that we are playing this card for is its GY effect which is that you can banish it can discard a card to search for an EARTH Machine monster from Deck. 3 Foolish Burial Goods which we are using to send Clockwork Night from Deck to GY. 3 Ancient Gear Fusion which Fusion Summons an Ancient Gear Fusion Monster from Extra Deck using monsters from hand or field as Fusion Materials, but if you use an Ancient Gear Golem or Ancient Gear Golem - Ultimate Pound you control as material, you can also use monsters in your Deck as material. This card is not once per turn, so if you draw multiple, you can Fusion Summon multiple times a turn, and since Ancient Gear Dark Golem becomes Ancient Gear Golem on field, you can Fuse using your Deck as well. 1 Ancient Gear Advance which adds an Ancient Gear Spell/Trap from your Deck to your hand on activation other than itself. As a soft once per turn, you can Tribute a monster to draw a card and also gives you the ability to Normal Summon Level 5 or higher monsters that are Ancient Gear Golem or that mention it for the rest of the turn. You also cannot set cards the turn you activate this card. We are playing this card as our 4th copy of Ancient Gear Fusion. You don't need to play this card, but it is nice to have this as an extra copy of Gear Fusion because I just like the feeling of Fusion Summoning 2 Ancient Gear Megaton Golems and using them to Xyz Summon Mereologic Aggregator. And finally, 3 Geartown which gives both players the ability to Normal Summon Ancient Gear monsters for 1 less Tribute and when it is destroyed and sent to the GY, you can Special Summon an Ancient Geare monster from hand, Deck, or GY with our targets being Reactor Dragon and Dark Golem where Dark Golem can actually be Special Summoned unlike the original Ancient Gear Golem and Ultimate Pound. 

Extra Deck: 1 Chaos Ancient Gear Giant which needs 4 Ancient Gears as Fusion Material which is comically easy with Dark Golem being treated as Ancient Gear Golem and also being able to search for Ancient Gear Fusion. It is unaffected by your opponent's Spell/Trap effects and your opponent cannot activate their monsters' effects during the Battle Phase. It can attack all monsters your opponent controls once each and it inflicts piercing damage. I feel like it would be criminal not to play this card when you are playing the new Ancient Gear support which practically screams make Chaos Giant with how easy it is to get Dark Golem onto field and search for Ancient Gear Fusion. 2 Ancient Gear Megaton Golem. Its effects really do not matter at all other than it being able to float into an Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem from Extra Deck if your opponent removes it from the field. It is just a Level 9 we are making for Rank 9 material. 1 Ultimate Ancient Gear Golem for Megaton to potentially float into. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. And finally, 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: It's a dark day when Ice Barrier has set combos
deck_description:
It might seem crazy, but I think that Ice Barrier Prediction Princess is a Deck that can utilize the newly limited Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Through a 2-card combo, you are able to get Ib onto the field, search for World Legacy Monstrosity, and Synchro Summon a Level 9 monster. However, this Deck is not that. Before I get to the Ice Barrier Deck with Ib, I want to show off Ice Barrier Prediction Princess featuring Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier as our Level 9 monster of choice. You can't go into it with Ib, but you can definitely go into it with pure Ice Barrier, especially with their new support from TW01. Trishula is a Level 9 WATER Dragon Synchro Monster that requires 1 Tuner and 2 or more non-Tuner monsters as Synchro Material. On Synchro Summon, Trishula can banish up to 1 card each from your opponent's hand, field, and GY with the card in their hand being banished at random. For a 3-card combo that gets you a single handloop and full Prediction Princess combo, that isn't too bad for all things considered. It still isn't great, but it's the thought that counts (probably). Our 3-card combo consists of Georgius, Swordsman of the Ice Barrier, Hexa Spirit of the Ice Barrier, and World Legacy Monstrosity. Normal Summon Hexa Spirit and use its effect to send Mirror Magic Master of the Ice Barrier (I swear, they are running out of names for these cards) to the GY and change its Level to 2. M^3 of the Ice Barrier triggers upon hitting the GY to search for General Wayne of the Ice Barrier. Since you control an Ice Barrier monster, Special Summon Georgius from hand and use its effect on Special Summon to Special Summon General Wayne from hand. Wayne triggers on Special Summon to search for Winds Over the Ice Barrier. Activate Winds to tribute Georgius to Special Summon a Level 2 non-Tuner Ice Barrier monster from Deck. Special Summon Zuijin of the Ice Barrier (which is the only one we are playing). 2+2+5=9, so Synchro Summon Trish and banish a card out of your opponent's hand. Activate Monstrosity and now you are on your way. With Ice Barrier having a card like Medallion of the Ice Barrier as a non-once-per-turn search for any Ice Barrier monster in addition to generic search tools like Pot of Prosperity, it is pretty easy to to actually get here as long as you have Monstrosity. And you also have cards like Foolish Burial to send M^3 and One for One to get Hexa Spirit from Deck. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can also Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during the End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's End Phase Effect. Her Flip Effect allows you to Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down, and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of monsters you control either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY if she was tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect allows you to search for a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck and while she is face-up on field, she gives all of your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent's effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler and 1 Pot of the Forbidden. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it. Pot of the Forbidden's Flip Effect allows you to choose 1 effect between drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, and looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card of your choice from it back into the Deck. For the Ice Barrier monsters, we are playing 1 General Wayne of the Ice Barrier, 3 Georgius, Swordsman of the Ice Barrier, 2 Mirror Magic Master of the Ice Barrier, 1 Zuijin of the Ice Barrier, and 3 Hexa Spirit of the Ice Barrier. I'll be ignoring their floogate/floodgate-adjacent effects because they frankly do not matter in the slightest. General Wayne can Special Summon himself from hand if your opponent controls a monster and you control an Ice Barrier Monster and on Normal or Special Summon, you can search for an Ice Barrier Spell/Trap from Deck. Because we are aiming to go first, we only play the 1 copy to search for it and Special Summon it by another effect. Georgius can Special Summon itself from hand if you control an Ice Barrier monster and if he is Normal or Special Summoned, you can Special Summon a Level 5 or lower Ice Barrier monster from hand or GY. Mirror Magic Master can Tribute 1 other Effect Monster you control to Special Summon up to 3 Ice Barrier Tokens (Aqua/WATER/Level 1/ATK 0/DEF 0) and then Mirror Magic Master's Level is increased by the same number of Tokens you Summoned but you cannot Special Summon monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of the turn except for WATER monsters. Also, if M^3 is sent to GY, you can add an Ice Barrier card that is banished or in your Deck to your hand except for M^3 of the Ice Barrier. You realistically only need to play 1, but you kind of really need to send it to GY, so playing 2 ensures that there is at least 1 in Deck to send to GY. Zuijin can Tribute itself to Special Summon a Level 5 or higher Ice Barrier from hand and if it is in GY, you can  target a Level 3 or higher WATER monster you control, reduce its Level by exactly 2 and Special Summon Zuijin from GY, but banish it when it leaves the field. We are only playing Zuijin as a Level 2 non-Tuner Ice Barrier to get from Deck with Winds Over the Ice Barrier, but you can realistically play any Level 2 non-Tuner Ice Barrier. It is just that Zuijin has a GY effect that can allow you to use it as an extender or something. Hexa Spirit can send a Level 3 or lower Ice Barrier monster from Deck to GY to have its Level become the Level of the sent monster until the end of the turn. We are using this effect to send Mirror Magic Master from Deck for a search while also modulating Hexa Spirit's Level.

For Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Medallion of the Ice Barrier which is a non-once-per-turn search for any Ice Barrier monster from Deck which is really good for consistency. 3 Winds Over the Ice Barrier which tributes any number of Ice Barrier monsters to Special Summon the same number of Level 4 or lower Ice Barrier monsters from Deck with different names. And during your Main Phase, you can banish this card from GY except during the turn it was sent there to target an Ice Barrier monster that is banished or in GY and add it back to hand. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down, and you can also banish it from your GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from your Deck face-down. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from hand or target a Level 9 monster you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than that monster but with different names. 1 One for One and 1 Foolish Burial. And finally, 3 Solemn Judgment. 

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Trishula, Zero Dragon of the Ice Barrier which needs a Tuner and 2 or more non-Tuners as Material. On Synchro Summon, it can banish up to 3 cards your opponent controls and if it is Synchro Summoned and destroyed by your opponent's card, you can Special Summon regular Trishula from Extra Deck or GY, make its ATK 3300 and halve the ATK of all face-up monsters your opponent controls and negate their effects. Big Trish is just something that Lancea can float into. 1 Lancea, Dragonic Ancestor of the Ice Spirit Mountain which can once per chain Special Summon an Ice Barrier monster from hand, Deck, Extra Deck, or GY if your opponent Special Summons a monster(s) and change a monster your opponent controls from Attack Position to Defense Position. This effect is a hard twice per turn. And if Lancea is Synchro Summoned and leaves the field by your opponent's card, you can Special Summon an Ice Barrier Synchro Monster from Extra Deck which is treated as a Synchro Summon. 1 Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier. 2 Herald of the Arc Light for Ritual searches. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 NIbiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Infinite Impermanence, and 3 Evenly Matched.
Dragons and Dogs band together in this deck! Filled with a variety of cards, this deck is great for new players looking to pull of big plays for realatively cheap!

deck_excerpt: Dinomorfia for Locals forfun controldecks control deck cheap budget
deck_description: I'll edit the results in a brief.

Playing style

The "Swordsoul" archetype is focused on Synchro Summoning. Instead of having archetypal Tuner monsters, "Swordsoul" cards instead have effects that Special Summon a Level 4 "Swordsoul Token" Tuner monster, which greatly increases the Deck's consistency compared to other Synchro Decks as there is no longer a need to search for Tuners. All the effects that Special Summon the "Swordsoul Token" apply the restriction that the player cannot Special Summon monsters from the Extra Deck except Synchro Monsters while the Token is on the field, in order to prevent abuse with other Extra Deck Summoning methods.

The archetype has a secondary focus on banishing cards. Several "Swordsoul" cards have effects that require banishing Wyrm monsters or "Swordsoul" cards from the GY as a cost, while other "Swordsoul" monsters banish the opponent's cards as a part of their effects. Synergizing with the former, the "Swordsoul" Spell/Trap Cards have effects that activate when banished; the Spells can modulate Levels, while the Traps can Special Summon a "Swordsoul Token".

The three main combo starters for the archetype are:

  • "Mo Ye", who summons a Token by revealing a Swordsoul/Wyrm card from hand
  • "Taia", who summons a Token by banishing a Swordsoul/Wyrm card from GY
  • "Longyuan", who summons itself and a Token by discarding another Swordsoul/Wyrm card

Because of their need other Wyrm monsters or "Swordsoul" cards as costs, the archetype is best played pure or with other Wyrm monsters.

The archetype's consistency and ceiling is further supported by its Spell/Traps and "Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous". "Swordsoul Emergence" is the archetype's searcher Spell that can also search generic Wyrm monsters for more boss monster options, "Swordsoul Sacred Summit" is a revival Spell, "Swordsoul Blackout" is a Normal Trap that trades 2-for-2, and "Incredible Ecclesia" is an additional searcher for "Swordsoul" monsters, making the deck incredibly consistent at starting its combos.

"Swordsoul" can easily make a variety of Level 8 or 10 Synchro monsters with disruptive or suppressive effects, as well as Levels 7, 9, and 11 Synchro monsters with their Spell/Traps' banish Level modulation effect. Their key Extra Deck monster however is "Swordsoul Grandmaster - Chixiao", an Extra Deck searcher able to search or banish any "Swordsoul" card from the Deck when summoned (who also has its own negation disruption effect), which enables further extension by searching for more "Swordsoul" starters or banishing a Trap to make a "Swordsoul Token", or to further strengthen the end board by searching a "Blackout" or "Emergence" (for it to search a generic Wyrm boss monster, like "Archnemeses Protos").

"Swordsoul" has good synergy with the "Tenyi" archetype, as both archetypes are Wyrm-based, supports Synchro Summoning, and the "Swordsoul Token" non-Effect Monster can enable the "Tenyi" Main Deck monsters' effects.

deck_excerpt: Are Tiaraments still strongest post 2024-banlist? I still think so!
deck_description:
Post January 2024 banlist, Tearlaments truly has something to lament about - and that is the loss of Kelbek and Agido! These two losses remove a substantial amount of milling power available to the strategy, unfortunately reducing what Tear can do since all they do is rely on mills. With this development, is the saying "Tiaraments truly strongest" still true? 
 
Thankfully, several mill tools are still available to Tear such as Zombie Vampire (made more accessible with the Horus Engine). Revolution Synchron coupled with Tuning can also mill and search various cards needed for combo! 
 
This strategy certainly isn't "dead," Tearlaments can still put up some crazy boards and a respectable fight! All Tearlaments requires is a little King of Games luck and skillful piloting to pull off!
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 

ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING 

 

Forming the core of this strategy, the Tearlament portion of this deck consists of 18 cards. 3 Perlereino allow you to search for the 9 maindeck Tearlament monsters, Scheiren, Havnis, Merrli, 3 Reinoheart and 3 Tearlaments Kashtira. 2 Scream, 2 Sulliek, 1 Heartbeat and 1 Grief search/recur for additional cards when milled. 

 

A HORUS package is used mainly for turboing out Zombie Vampire for mills and is composed of 6 cards - 3 Imsety, 1 Hapi, and 2 King's Sarcophagus. 

 

A SYNCHRON package is used, composed of 2 Revolution Synchrons and 3 Tuning so enable the summon of Visas Amritra and mill some cards. If you resolve Tuning and Revolution Synchron, it mills a total of two extra cards while searching extra cards!

 

A KASHTIRA package of 1 Wraithsoth (often the search target for AFD), 1 Fenrir and 3 Kashtira Tearlaments are used.

 

2 King of the Swamp and 1 Polymerization as a search target is included, since they function as specific names when used for fusion material in the GY when fusing with Tearlaments. This gives you access to strong fusion monsters like Rulkallos and Grapha.

 

You may have noticed that there are hardly any handtraps or generic staples in this deck. The theory behind this build of Tearlaments is that it has so much gas that it can play through all of your opponent's interruptions just fine, as long as your graveyard is accessible and you aren't floodgated to death.

 

40 cards are used to ensure this strategy is as consistent and compact as possible. In addition to bricking less, the mills will have much better results than bigger Tearlaments variants because of the deck's compact size. 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN 

 

Tearlaments' gameplan is to mill as much as possible to trigger Tearlament effects. Tearlament monsters are ideal to mill as much as possible to turbo out powerful fusion monsters like Grapha and Rulkallos to protect your combo lines. Like every Tearlaments strategy, this deck aims to mill as much as possible and gain beneficial effects from those mills. The reliance on mills makes this strategy unpredictable and luck dependant, meaning that there are hardly any straightforward combos. Combos are hand/mill dependent - leaving the rest of the game up to the duelists individual skill, decision making and mental fortitude (that's the Tearlaments is regarded as a difficult to pilot deck). Tearlaments are also infamous for requiring a great deal of skill, since the pilot has to be aware of the various interactions they have in the GY and the amount of cards left in their maindeck. 

 

First, you do as much milling as possible to get searches triggered and your GY set-up. Your boards vary, but generally have a mix of Rulkallo's summon negate, Grapha's omni-negate, Kaleido-Heart's shuffle, Sulliek's negate, Perlereino's pop and Ishizu card's graveyard shuffling. 

 

Going second, this deck's gas ploughs through interruption and negates (especially if you chainblocked to guarantee effects to go through). This deck can also side in a ton of boardbreakers and still remain consistent. Best cards to side out are your Synchron package (Tuning + Revolution Synchron) and Tearlament Grief + Hearbeat.

 
Here is the deck's new fancy combo featuring Ancient Fairy Dragon, Revolution Synchron and Visas Amritara:
 
Level 4 monster + Revolution Synchron = Field spell search, +1000 LP gain, Tearlament spell/trap search. 
  1. Do your opening plays to search and mill to set up your GY. 
  2. Normal summon your level 4 monster. If it has an effect, activate the effect. 
  3. Synchro summon Ancient Fairy Dragon (AFD) using a Level 4 monster + Revolution Synchron. 
  4. If there is a field spell on the board, activate AFD's effect to gain 1000 LP and search a fieldspell from deck. 
  5. Special summon Revolution Synchron from the GY with it' effect and mill 1 card.
  6. Synchro summon Visas Amritara using AFD + Revolution Synchron (now a level 1). 
  7. Activate Visas Amritara's on-summon effect to search for a needed Tearlaments Spell/Trap. 
  8. Keep milling and fusing in the GY until you resolved all effects and your field is full of boss monsters!

GENERAL TIPS

  • Mill as much as possible when before fusion summoning so you have as much options in the GY as fusion material as possible. If you milled King of the Swamps and Tearlament girls, you've hit a home run since they fusion summon Grapha or Rulkallos!
  • Horus cards are incredible at cracking established boards and can out powerful boss monsters that have negates. 
  • Visas Amritara can trigger your Tearlaments monsters GY effects by destroying them on the field. For example, Amritara destroys Kaleido-Heart on the field -> Kaleido-Heart summons itself from GY and sends Tear girl to GY -> tear girl fusion summons using materials from GY. Amritara allows for additional extension!
  • Any Tearlaments strategy is infamous for requiring a great deal of skill to pilot, since the duelists is required to know all the various interactions that goes on in the GY, and to remember how many cards are left in their deck - the while considering how the opponent will react to the plays. This deck is not easy, so practice makes perfect with Tearlaments. 
     
    Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

CONCLUDING REMARKS

 
I personally still find the Tearlaments playstyle quite fun - the randomness of the mills and the dopamine hit when the mills actually succeed feel so goooood (only if mills pop off)! I like how this deck actually requires skill - it rewards the pilot's decision making, resource management and situational awareness. I personally find it so badass and satisfying pulling everything off! 
 
Despite the catastrophic loss of Agido and Kelbek, Tearlaments can still put up a respectable board! The Horus engine somewhat replaces the loss of the Ishizu package fairly well with its boardbreaking capability and mills with Zombie Vampire. 
 
Tearlaments is the posterchild of archetypes "suffering from success" as they've had all their good cards and starters banned (RIP Chaos Ruler and rest in PISS Ishizu cards). COPIUM, dedication and creativity are the only things keeping Tearlaments players alive in this day and age - and now that is demonstrated with the new support post-AGOV/banlist! The question is, can Tearlaments continue to top despite the repeating hits to this strategy? Only time will tell!

 

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: A Supreme King Z-Arc deck I made for fun with some interesting tech cards.
deck_description: The goal of this deck is get one of the Supreme King Gates into your pendulum zone, then summon Supreme King Gate Magician to search one of the trap cards and summon Z-Arc. Your Supreme King Gate cards can be searched by scaling Supreme King Gate Magician, or by summoning Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm. The latter can be done using the normal summon, or by sending it to the graveyard with an empty field. Supreme King Dragon Lightwurm is your best high pendulum scale, and can be used with another level 4 monster to summon a level 4 synchro monster or a level 7 for a rank 7 xyz monster (using its scale effect for the latter). Destrudo is an alternative target for Dragon Shrine, since Darkwurm won't work in the graveyard with a monster on the field. Clear Wing Synchro Dragon should normally be banished with Soul of the Supreme Celestial King, but can also be summoned off a level four and an Ash Blossom or Destrudo. Supreme King Gate Infinity is not normally run in this deck due to its restrictive pendulum effect, but I chose to run it in order to use Gate Zero's effect to search a fusion spell such as Super Polymerization or Destiny Fusion. Effect Veiler is chosen over Imperm because it can be used with a level 7 monster to synchro summon. Radian is chosen over other Kaijus because its attribute allows it to be banished from the grave to summon a Chaos monster, removed with Super Polymerization and Starving Venom, or Pendulum Summoned even if Darkwurm is in the scales, and its level is also useful for xyz summons should you pendulum summon it. Odd Eyes Arc Pendulum Dragon is chosen over other "Pendulum Dragon" monsters because it is a level seven, has good stats and pendulum scale, and is a normal mosnter that can be sent to the grave with Dragon Shrine for free deck thinning. Supreme King Odd-Eyes is intended to be Special Summoned from the deck using the non-negated Z-Arc from Soul of the Supreme Celestial King. Odd-Eyes Arcray Dragon can be summoned in place of the negated Z-Arc from Soul of the Supreme King should your opponent try to play around it by avoiding the use of spell cards, and it its name clause allows you to keep the trap in the grave online indefinitely. Book of Eclipse and Book of Moon are interesting experimental inclusions because they can turn a Z-Arc summoned with Soul of the Supreme King face down, allowing its Raigeki effect to go off without being negated. It will then not return to the extra deck on your end step, nor will it be negated if flipped face up again. Some of the Side Deck cards, including Destiny Hero Plasma, the Chaos monsters, and Supreme King Clear Wing, are included for only testing purposes rather than as serious options for tournament play.

deck_excerpt: Snakes and Thunder, Connected by Daybreak!
deck_description:
So, Ogdoadic and Spright. Very different archetypes. How are they connected together? -Ogdoadic Daybreak. Daybreak tributes 1 reptile and summons a token for every 2 levels that monster had. This Card is actually kinda amazing, and even has a effect to return the usually dead -Nunu, the Ogdoadic Remnant that are banished to your deck, and send a Reptile from your deck to the GY. Daybreak has a thousand uses, from spamming your field with Tokens by using Curse + Nauya / Nephilabyss, or even tributing a level 2 reptile like Lamia to send Lamia to the gy and replace it. Spright uses these level 2 tokens (Reptiles don't really care that they are level 2 usually) to summon themselves, as ammunition for Red/Carrot, and for a link summon. 

Deck can go both first and second. Triple Tactics is a must, as based on your hand, just 1 Ash makes you pass your turn. Droll doesn't affect this deck a lot. Nibiru on the other hand, is the true counter to this deck. The Monsters you end on don't have a huge enough Stat to give you a huge enough Nibiru token, but with just a rock token in your field, you can't summon Nunu back on your turn.

This deck, and Ogdoadic itself can run a million options. Therion Empress was my most successful, as it was a easy level 8. Other Therions are raw bricks though, and makes using them risky. So, I just played 1-2 Empress, since it's the second easier level 8 reptile to get out.

This deck doesn't actually "brick." I say that beacuse Starting with a spright in your hand without some kind of reptile starter (Snake Rain, Nauya, Nunu, Or even Water Lily) makes for one of the worst possible hands in this deck. Another reason to run TTT.

Important Cards: 

• -Ogdoadic Daybreak (Level 2 token spammer), -Reptilianne Lamia (Best Tuner in the Deck, Connects Spright and Ogdoadic together just like Daybreak)

deck_excerpt: Ancient Gear has 1-card combos now hooray
deck_description: Historically a blind second OTK strategy, Ancient Gear as a pure strategy now has plays going first (sort of).  Opening any 1 of Wyvern, Frame, Advance, or Foolish Burial Goods can now end on a 3300 Atk or 4400 Atk monster unaffected by monster effects, and while these lines are vulnerable to interruption like Ash, Imperm, or Droll, drawing multiples of these starters can allow the deck to play through some interruption now.  Foolish Burial Goods in particular can be flexed into adding Therion "King" Regulus to your end board if you drew another starter.  The only thing this deck needs now is a reliable way to put 2 Golems on board to pair with Ancient Gear Fusion and Ancient Gear Duel, which is doable with Commander + a starter but isn't as consistent as you'd like currently.  Overall, deck probably isn't tier 1, but at least with the 1-card combos it allows the engine to be smaller to incorporate more handtraps and board breakers, so it's got a chance.

deck_excerpt: Infernoble Noble Knight Synchron Battlin' Boxer Mannadium
deck_description:
The Infernoble knights are rising from the ashes with the help of some new friends!

Deck Strategy:

I thought the deck was dead with the loss of our shawty-- Isolde. To be honest, the deck is much worse, ESPECIALLY if you don't want to spend 400 big ones on the Diabellestar engine. 

Fortunately, some special sauce is here to spice things up again.

The deck has a much harder time getting Angelica's Ring onto the field after the ban, which is key to preventing some of the deck's biggest weaknesses like Lightning Storm and Dark Ruler. Instead, Assault Synchron will help us run throught the Mannadium line to set up a Reframing, offering us a counter-trap omni negate.

On the other hand, Tuning plus Rev Synchron gets us more cards milled into the graveyard, and even gives us access to the legendary Power Tool Dragon. He can get us a guaranteed durendal, then use rev sunchron again out of the grave to turn him into Crystal Wing. That helps us smell what the Rock is cooking-- and play under Nibiru.

Finally-- Battlin' Boxers make a big impact by getting free bodies on the field. Uppercutter makes a great normal summon into sparrer-- allowing you to make a free rank 4. My favorite play is to use the two 4's seperately if you have access to Revolution Synchron. Use the Rev and a boxer to make Power Tool Dragon, then reborn the Rev and use another boxer to make our shawty Angelica. It's extra nifty if you mill an Infernoble Knight with the effect of Rev!

Ideal End Boards:

The best end board you can achieve would include two copies of Charles, one Gearfried, and one Amritara. This sets you up with two spell negates, a monster negate, and an omni-negate that can stop Dark Ruler. If you have Roland in the grave, make sure to equip him to Charles on your opponent's turn for a free destroy!

Another option is having Two Charles, one Gearfried, and Crystal Wing on your end board. While it may not be as diverse as the first option, it does play safer under the Rock.

Some Extra Tips: 

Sometimes you could end up with a leftover Power Tool Dragon, which can be awkward. If you have an extra Assault Synchron, he can go straight into Power Tool Braver Dragon for a nice monster negate. Otherwise... S:P is always cracked.

Watch out for that Warrior lock that comes from the incredible Noble Arms Museum! It can cut off your Mannadium and Power Tool combos if you aren't careful. 

When running the Mannadium line, think carefull on how you use Trisukta. Normally you will want to get you hands on that Reframing from Amritara-- but do remember to respect the Rock. Trisukta can synchro with any other level 4 to just make Baronne. Better safe than sorry.

Sales ban is for Droll and Lock Bird. We all know he is a menace for this deck, that's nothing new. While this version plays a bit better through D Shifter, Droll is arguably even more impactful now because of the boxers. Perfectly balanced, as all things should be.

End:

While Infernobles have seen better days, the loss of Isolde is not the end for the Knights. I'm sure there are stronger builds made with the DIabellestar engine, so make sure to take a look at those too. If you are more on the budget side-- give this build a try. The boards it can build may surprise you!

deck_excerpt: I'm glad this deck is actually really solid right now
deck_description:
My current VW build for 2024

 

There's a few interesting choices here and there, but I find quite a bit of consistency in this build

 

Side deck can really just be whatever you have avaliable

 

Handtraps are interchangable

- The Syncro Monsters are there to use when you are using "Dogmatika Punishment"

- The purpose of this deck is to almost always be able to call out Eldlich but if you aren't able to, there's almost always a way to defend yourself until you can actually call him out.

- While he is called out from the grave by sacrificing one Spell/Trap card you control, he is immune to most card/monster effects for the next two turns.

- If you want to use any of the polymerization cards to call out "Eldlich The Mad Golden Lord" you will first have to call out "Eldlich The Golden Lord" and use one of the three trap cards "Conquestador of the Golden Land", "Guardian of the Golden Land" or "Huaquero of the Golden Land" because they are the only 5+ level zombie monsters you can use to do so. If you use Super Polymerization, the opponent has to have some applicable monster in their field in order to do so.

- If you are using any of the archetypes of Eldlich the Golden Lord, you first have to have him as a monster and than activate "Conquestador of the Golden Land", "Guardian of the Golden Land" or "Huaquero of the Golden Land" and their effects are braken down as simple as:

- "Conquestador of the Golden Land" destroys one face-up card

- "Guardian of the Golden Land" lowers one face-up monsters ATK down to 0

- "Huaquero of the Golden Land" banishes one card from either players graveyard

TIP: Their effects can be negated!

The best combo you can do with this deck is:

- Call out two "Eldlich the Golden Lord" by using any of the cards that you need to do so and than sacrifice them to call out "Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max", use his effect to deal 2000 life damage to the opponent, than sacrifice him to call out "Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut" and use his effect to gain 2000 ATK points, go to battle phase and deal the remaining 6000 damage to your opponents life points.
