deck_excerpt: There will never be a better Dark Magician Deck
deck_description: Absolutely perfect Dark Magician deck and it's even somewhat viable competitively.

Just a Dinomorphia deck that I found and made modifications to. Unfortunately, Dinomorphia isn't really viable as it heavily relies on trap cards, and it heavily loses you life points. It's optimal to lose as many as possible though, but that again, is a double edged sword. It makes it very easy for the opponent to just randomly pick you off with a stray effect or attack. It's key to get your fusion monsters out as soon as possible, especially Rexterm, as its effect makes it so your opponent can't activate monster effects on the field whose ATK points are equal to or higher than your LP. In conjunction with it's quick effect that makes all ATK points of your opponent equal to your LP after paying half of your LP, it makes for a good combo. And if your LP are already low, it makes it very frustrating for your opponent to get rid of it, unless they have effects they activate in the hand/GY or with spells/traps. There are some changes that can be made. A new Dinomorphia trap card, Dinomorphia Intact, can replace Solemn Strike on top of using its GY effect to negate battle damage if banished.

I typically use Dinomorphia Frenzy/ or Domain to get Kentregina out and use her effect to banish a Dinomorphia trap card and use its effect to get out Rexterm. Though if you get Ultimate Conductor Tyranno in your hand, you can use the same effect of getting Kentregina out, and then banishing those 2 dinosaur monsters to bring him out. He is great support as his effect destroys one of your monsters in your hand or field, and then flip all your opponents monsters to face down defense position. And then he gets to attack each monster anyway, but he can deal 1000LP to your opponent if he targets a defense position monster, and it destroys it without having to actually fight it. NOTE: he just has to target it for an attack. There are also some XYZ monsters to help round things out and add more variety. Dolkka and Laggia can be summoned with 2 of any of the LVL 4 Dinosaur monsters and are summoned at your discretion. Also, of course, Utopia, Utopia Prime, and then Zeus. Durendal is a placeholder. I legitamately had nothing else to throw in the extra deck that made sense, and Master Duel just included it randomly at some point, and I have been too lazy to swap it out. SO, just ignore it.

In conclusion, I'm not terribly good at Yu-Gi-Oh, but I really enjoy the archetype regardless as it's different from what other decks do. As well as being a little anti-meta, it has cool monsters (Kentregina <3) and a unique playstyle. It's very satifying to win as you are constantly low on LP and are always making a comback. Either way, give it a try if you are so inclined! :)

deck_excerpt: Looking at Karakuri's & Superheavy Samurai's Level 9 Synchros
deck_description:
I still have a lot of Level 9 Synchro Monsters to cover, but some fit comfortably into some of my other Synchro Level 9-focused Prediction Princess Decks. Ally of Justice Field Marshal and Mist Wurm have the same Synchro Material requirements as Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier and fit perfectly into Ice Barrier Prediction Princess because there is no conceivable way that Ally of Justice or Mist Valley can make these Synchros turn 1 with just their own archetype's cards unless we get like a TW02 and get actually good support for them. Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon and Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon are immediately crossed off the list because a Blue-Eyes Prediction Princess Deck is not possible. Imagine realizing that Blue-Eyes Abyss Dragon can search for any Ritual Spell on Special Summon, allowing you to Synchro it and a Level 1 Tuner into Spirit Dragon. But Spirit Dragon prevents both players from Special Summoning 2+ monsters at the same time. Alright, so let's just tag it out for Azure-Eyes. BUT WAIT! Azure-Eyes has a MANDATORY effect that activates when it is Special Summoned to prevent your Dragon monsters from being targeted or destroyed by card effects. This means that neither player can target your Dragons, so you can't even target it with Monstrosity. WHY IS IT MANDATORY? Then, we have Yoko, the Graceful Mayakashi. I am a big Mayakashi fan believe it or not. I have Eldlich Mayakashi as a Deck both in Master Duel and IRL. I even have Yuki-Onna, the Absolute Zero Mayakashi as my pfp. But that means that I already know that you cannot make a Mayakashi Prediction Princess Deck. Cards like Dakki, the Graceful Mayakashi who is the main Synchro climb-enabler for the Deck prevents you from Special Summoning from the Extra Deck except for Mayakashi monsters if you use its effect and other cards like Hajun, the Winged Mayakashi and Yuki-Musume, the Ice Mayakashi have continuous effects that prevent you from Special Summoning from the Extra Deck except for Mayakashi monsters. Yoko is generic so you can just throw it into any Prediction Princess Deck that makes a Level 9 Synchro, but you just can't make a Mayakashi Prediction Princess Deck.

Moving onto today's topic: I completely forgot about Superheavy Samurai when it came to me theorizing the easiest ways to make Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. With the presence of Superheavy Samurai, pretty much any Prediction Princess Deck that is focused around making a Synchro Level 9 as your Level 9 monster of choice can go through a line to make Ib to search for World Legacy Monstrosity before getting to that Level 9 Synchro Monster. However, that would result in like a dozen Superheavy Samurai Prediction Princess Decks with a different flavor of Level 9 Synchro monster each time which is not what I want to be doing. This is going to be the only Prediction Princess Deck with a Superheavy Samurai engine to access both Ib and a Level 9 Synchro, and we are focusing on the two archetypes that really need the usage of Superheavy Samurai: Superheavy Samurai and Karakuri. We are taking a look at 2 Level 9 monsters today: Superheavy Samurai Beast Kyubi and Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N "Bureibu". I'm going to be very real here: These are 2 bad targets for World Legacy Monstrosity on field. They are both EARTH Attribute which means that you cannot Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck if you target either of them with Monstrosity. And before someone says to make Reprodocus to change the Attribute of either one since SHS has the capability to get enough Link Material onto field to do so, Monstrosity checks for original Type and Attribute, so there is no side-stepping that fact. We are playing a Cloudcastle as an alternative Level 9 whose Type and Attribute are capable of getting Bibliomuse off of Monstrosity, but we are playing cards for both the Kyubi and Bureibu aspects of the Deck. Full combo is Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi and a Level 4 non-Tuner or a Level 1 non-Tuner. Scale Wakaushi and use its Pend Effect to scale Superheavy Samurai Monk Big Benkei from Deck and Special Summon Wakaushi. Let's say that you drew a Level 4 non-Tuner in Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster. Using Monk Benkei's Pend Effect, search for Superheavy Samurai Soulhorns. Equip Soulgaia Booster and Soulhorns to Wakaushi and use their effects to Special Summon themselves. Synchro Wakaushi and Soulhorns into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Ib CL 1 to search for World Legacy Monstrosity and Wakaushi CL 2 to Scale itself from face-up Extra Deck to Chain Block your search. Now we have 3 different paths we can take. If you are like “Yeah, I want Bibliomuse access…”, Synchro Ib and Soulgaia Booster into Cloudcastle to target it with Monstrosity. If you want to go with the Superheavy Samurai path, Synchro Ib and Soulgaia Booster into Superheavy Samurai Beast Kyubi and target it with Monstrosity to get our Level 9 targets from Deck, being Sacred Arch-Airknight Parshath and Moisture Creature. We have Aggregator access now, and if you drew Gizmek Makami, the Ferocious Fanged Fortress, you can Pendulum Summon it and use its effect to discard a monster to search for Bibliomuse. If you want to go the Karakuri route, Synchro Ib and Soulgaia Booster into Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N “Bureibu”. On Synchro Summon, Bureau Special Summons Karakuri Gama mdl 4624 “Shirokunishi” from Deck. Target Bureibu with Monstrosity to get Arch Parshath and Moisture Creature from Deck and if you drew Makami, you can Pend Summon it to search for Bibliomuse. The benefit of going for Bureibu is that you can Xyz into Mereologic Aggregator with Arch Parshath and Moisture Creature and leave Bureibu on field. From here, you can Synchro Bureibu and Shirokunishi into Baronne de Fleur or Link off Shirokunishi and your Aggregator (with Herald of the Arc Light attached) for I:P Masquerena or S:P Little Knight and use Shirokunishi’s GY Quick Effect to banish itself to change the Battle Position of Bureibu during your opponent’s turn to trigger Bureibu to target and banish a card your opponent controls. Is this Deck good? If you ditch going for Bureibu or SHS Beast Kyubi and focus on Synchroing a Level 9 Synchro that you can actually target with Monstrosity to get Bibliomuse out from the Deck, you can ditch Shirokunishi, the Makami’s, Arch Parshath, and Moisture Creature from Deck, throw in the second Deus-X Krawler (or a Pot of the Forbidden) and put in more handtraps. Now you have quite the Deck on your hands. You have Prediction Princess combo to end on Deus-X and potentially other Flips going first and have a good amount of handtraps to feel comfortable going second. I don’t hate the Deck, but I feel like it takes away from the spirit of Superheavy Samurai in it being a big ol’ wombo combo deck that goes through a multitude of Extra Deck monsters and Extra Deck Monster Types.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field dace-up or face-down and can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself from the GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and it searches for a Level 9 with a different Type and Attribute than itself if destroyed on field. 1 Sacred Arch-Airknight Parshath which has an absolutely ridiculous Summoning Condition. If you activate a Counter Trap Card or negate the activation of a Spell/Trap Card or monster effect except during the damage step, you can banish 2 other Fairy monsters from your hand, field, and/or GY as cost to Special Summon this card from hand or GY. Does it do anything on Summon? Nope. It inflicts piercing and when it inflicts battle damage to your opponent, you can add a Parshath card or a Counter Trap from Deck to hand. 1 Moisture Creature which can be Tribute Summoned with 3 Tributes and if you do, you pop all of your opponent’s Spell/Traps. Moisture Creature and Sacred Arch Airknight Parshath are only in here as funny Level 9 targets to get out from the Deck if you decide to go into Bureibu or SHS Beast Kyubi. These will never get their own Prediction Princess Deck because they are both Fairies so you can’t target them with Monstrosity to get Bibliomise from Deck. And it’s not like they actually do anything on Summon that benefits you. Moisture Creature doesn’t belong to an archetype or Deck and while Arch Parshath does belong to Counter Fairy, it’s not like he searches anything on Summon so we aren’t even going to try for him. For the Superheavy Samurai monsters: 2 Superheavy Samurai Monk Big Benkei, 3 Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi, 1 Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster, 3 Superheavy Samurai Soulpiercer, 1 Superheavy Samurai Soulhorns, 3 Superheavy Samurai Motorbike, and 3 Superheavy Samurai Stealthy. We are using Monk Benkei only for its Pendulum Effect which is if you control a SHS monster, you can add a SHS Soul monster from Deck to hand. We are always using this effect to get something like Soulgaia Booster or Soulpiercer if we need a Level 4 non-Tuner for our combo or getting Soulhorns if we need a Level 1 non-Tuner. Wakaushi’s Pend Effect is that if you have no Spell/Traps in your GY, you can place a SHS Pend Monster except itself from Deck in your Pend Zone and Special Summon Wakaushi from its scale. And the only one of its monster effects that we are using is Wakaushi being able to scale itself from face-up Extra Deck if it is used as Synchro Material and sent there. Soulgaia Booster targets a SHS monster you control and equips itself from hand or field to that monster, and if it is equipped to a monster by its own effect, you can Special Summon it. Its other effects are not exactly relevant as we are just using this card as a Level 4 non-Tuner we are able to Summon. Soulpiercer also targets a SHS you control to equip itself from hand or field to that monster, and if it is sent from field to GY, you can add a SHS monster from Deck to hand other than itself. This effect is not once per turn. Soulhorns also targets a SHS you control and equips itself from hand or field to it, and while it is equipped by its own effect, you can Special Summon it. Motorbike can discard itself if you have no Spell/Traps in GY to add a Superheavy Samurai monster from Deck to hand except itself. It’s other effect allows you to target a Machine you control to increase its Level by 2, but we aren’t exactly Synchro comboing like you would normally in SHS, so this isn’t relevant. Stealthy is an inherent Special Summon from hand if you have no Spell/Traps in your GY once per turn. And since it is a Level 1 monster, it can also meet your Level 1 non-Tuner requirement. Also, if you have no Spell/Traps in GY, you can Quick Effect Tribute it to target a Spell/Trap in your opponent’s GY and set it to your field but banish it when it leaves the field. This effect will rarely come up, but supposedly if your opponent Imperms you and you already have a Level 1 non-Tuner other than Stealthy in rotation, you can use this to get another piece of interruption for yourself. 1 Karakuri Gama mdl 4624 “Shirokunishi” which can Quick Effect banish itself from GY and target a Karakuri monster you control to change its Battle Position. Again, we are getting this from Deck with Bureibu if we decide to go for him and can either act as a Level 1 Tuner to go into Baronne or be used alongside Bureibu as interruption. 3 Gizmek Makami, the Ferocious Fanged Fortress which you would usually Pendulum Summon in this Deck if you really need to use its effect. On Normal or Special Summon, you can discard a card to search for a monster whose ATK equals its DEF except Makami which gets you Bibliomuse if you need access for her in a situation where you went for Kyubi or Bureibu. 2 Kashtira Fenrir and 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring as our last monsters and our non-engine pieces. If this Deck wasn’t built around Synchro Summoning specifically Superheavy Samurai Beast Kyubi or Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N “Bureibu” to act as targets for World Legacy Monstrosity, we would be able to play more non-engine as we would have more space for it if we get rid of the cards we are playing specifically for Kyubi and Bureibu purposes.

For Spell/Traps, we only have 5 of them. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction, 1 World Legacy Monstrosity, and 1 World Legacy Succession. Underworld Ritual can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. Monstrosity can either Special Summon a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9’s from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than it but with different names. Succession Special Summons a monster from GY to your zone a Link Monster points to. It’s not necessary, but if you draw Monstrosity, I would like another target to search with Ib, especially since Succession getting you back a Level 9 can benefit you so much.

Extra Deck: Before I get into it, I just want to say that I know that Superheavy Samurai can make a wild number of interactions through several different monsters that they can churn out from the Extra Deck. I’ve played the Deck on several occasions, but understand that this is Superheavy Samurai Prediction Princess. A normal Prediction Princess endboard has a monster in the EMZ and 3 monsters in your Main Monster Zones, and once we get to the opponent’s turn, all of our Monster Zones are filled. We can’t play any more Extra Deck monsters that SHS is capable of making because we literally just do not have the board space to actually Summon any of them. First off, we are not playing Master of Ham which makes this list TCG legal at the current time. We are playing Superheavy Samurai - a Deck that requires you to have no Spell/Traps in GY, so it is best to play none or just the ones that you need depending on what your Deck is trying to accomplish. Besides, we can search for Monstrosity to get Bibliomuse from Deck, so Master of Ham isn’t doing much either way. 1 Baronne de Fleur. 1 Cloudcastle. 1 Karakuri Super Shogun mdl 00N “Bureibu” which Special Summons a Karakuri from Deck on Synchro Summon and also can target and banish a card your opponent controls if a Karakuri monster(s) you control have their battle position changed. 1 Superheavy Samurai Beast Kyubi. Its effects literally do not matter. TLDR, it is just a ginormous beater for Superheavy Samurai. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Newly limited and back in the game. On Synchro Summon, she can add a World Legacy card from Deck to hand and if she is Synchro Summoned and sent from field to GY, you can Special Summon a World Chalice monster from Deck or GY which we will not be doing. However, her first effect searches us World Legacy Monstrosity which makes me so incredibly happy that Synchro-focused Prediction Princess Decks have a way to search for Monstrosity now because it just means that you just need to stop by Ib before getting to said Level 9 Synchro in your combo. It really does help. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 3 Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay, 1 Kurikara Divincarnate, and 3 Effect Veiler.

Here is a cool little deck revolving around our lovely guide from Duel Links, at least thats where I saw her, the Tour Guide! I did not know she was part of an archetype so it was pretty nice to make a deck around her. Plus we have some other cards like the Prediction Princesses in there. Enjoy!

Hey, whatsup? In this deck, we will boost the ATK of "Dark Crusader" and perform FTK with Number 43. Let's see...

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup Primal Seed loop.

2) Special Summon Dark Crusader...

  • If discarded via Dugares/Ravenous, use "Monster Reborn".
  • If in-hand, use Saryuja.

3) Special Summon Sharnga >>> Vata >>> Caligo, in explained order. Then, XYZ Summon Number 43 with these three and destroy it with Offerings. Revive the trio with "Monster Reborn" and do it again for second Number 43. In short, make sure 2 x Number 43 monsters are present.

4) "Dark Crusader" gains ATK, if you discard a DARK monster from your hand to GY. With "Pot of Avarice" refilling your deck with DARK monsters alongside draw power, it won't be a huge deal. "Pot of Generosity" is here to let you enable "Pot of Avarice".

5) If the ATK of Crusader is higher than your opponent's LP, activate "Mystik Wok" on Crusader and choose its ATK. By healing yourself, 2 x Number 43 monsters are ready to convert said gain into damage to FTK your opponent.

A War Rock deck I've had average success with. Primarily against decks that rely on the Battle Phase. Don't have much of a problem out pacing them in that sense but if your opponent is more of a manipulative/combo or stun deck... well... you're going to have to make your own side deck for that. I usually run this deck when I'm in a fightin' mood and it's to battle or be doomed trying. Fortia is key to be on the field at first fight and getting in direct with Bashileos is key to winning. If you find hitting in direct with Bashileos is what your main win is then you can run three. 

I recommend keeping some dice on hand to track the number of times you've increased your monsters by 200 as I often found myself with 4 to 5 on board and it helps to keep track which increment of 200 you're at because the two Big Boys are quick effects that activate before the damage step and the others activate after damage calculation.

Another strategy is to use Orpis to get Skyler or Meteoragon into the grave and summon them with War Rock Spirit as they have no built in easy summon effect like the others. Despite playing this deck a fair bit I still can't decide on the ratios of Mountains, Spirit, and Dignity and the traps. If you're going against a combo deck with lots of monster effects run more Dignity since its not a once per turn. If they also blow up your stuff a lot during the main phase maybe run more Big Blows. You can take out Twin Twisters if they're not running back row but some of my game wins were disrupting backrow and hitting in for game. It can also facilitate a Warrior to grave for Spirit.

The side deck really is just an ongoing ratio tester. I've never actually purused making it into a proper side deck. (I play on a very small budget) 

Quaking Mirror Force can be swapped out for anything but I've found it really good if my opponent actualy makes a board stronger than mine I flip them all face down and attack into them on the next turn so the opponent can't activate any grave effects (or effects in general since they're face down) they might have before they end their turn.

I haven't faced any of the newer decks/threats with this deck since I haven't used it in a while and I play in a very casual format where no one uses cards over 20$ so I have no clue how well this deck runs against stuff like that.

Final notes, the extra deck is more of a situational thing that you restort to in desperation. (the link monster is more there just for that 500 ATK boos in a pinch and I rarely use anyone but Gandiva or Excalibur for big damage) Or that's at least how I found it. War Rocks really like each other being on board and hit hard with their own effects (and ATK) as is so I rarely find myself going into the extra deck. Probably another reason why I lose so much but I play on a tight budget so this is what I use. A very cheap deck and fun to play if you like going to war. Yugioh does feel less about the battle phase and more of a build up the board for one hit kill so maybe it's out of date. If you have any modern success with it I'd love to hear it in the comments.

deck_excerpt: Number 43 FTK ft. Time Wizard of Tomorrow
deck_description:
So, you might have heard of "Time Wizard of Tomorrow", where you need to guess the coin call right in order to blast your opponent. Should you do it wrong, you will be dead but what if I told you that you can win either way with a crafty setup? Let's find out!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Plant five plants to opposing side with "Black Garden", which will be replaced with bigger monsters thanks to "Mystic Box" and "Monster Reborn". After that, activate "Lair of Darkness" and make sure Dugares is in your GY.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to have Primal Seed setup ready. As long as you don't banish Ancient and Librarian by accident via Chaos Emperor, you will be fine.

3) After you have Link Summoned Saryuja, Special Summon "Fusion Parasite", letting you Fusion Summon. Use Parasite + Saryuja as materials and place it on Main Monster Zone (MMZ).

4) If you have Swirl + Ghost in-hand, activate Swirl to Fusion Summon Oracle by using Swirl + Ghost as materials in-hand and place it on Extra Monster Zone (EMZ). Also, activate "Forbidden Dress" on Oracle to not let it be destroyed. You will see why eventually.

5) Since Swirl + Ghost were sent to GY thanks to what you did in #4, revive them with "Monster Reborn" in addition to Formula. With Formula converted into DARK monster thanks to "Lair of Darkness" active in #1, you have 3 x Level 2 DARK monsters. It means you can bring forth Number 43 by using them as materials. Also, activate Number 43 to equip Dugares to not let Number 43 be destroyed. You will see why later on.

6) Time to fill both sides with beefy monsters because "Time Wizard of Tomorrow" can deal equal to half the total original ATK of destroyed face-up monsters upon trigger. You can see the picture as reference below but I'll also take notes as well:

  • Monsters were revived and given to opposing side with "Monster Reborn" and "Mystic Box", respectively, by replacing plants.
  • Here is the maximum possible damage output. Mind you, any changes done by Saryuja/Garden and alike doesn't count, seen in the description of "Time Wizard of Tomorrow":
    • Opponent = 2800 + 2400 + 2200 + 2100 + 2200 = 11700
    • You = 3000 + 2500 + 2000 + 2000 = 9500
    • Total = (11700 + 9500) / 2 = 10600 >>> Lethal!
  • Make sure you revive monsters illustrated above, if you play 2 x Upstart Goblin cards. These are all of highest ATK monsters you have in your arsenal but if you go second and your opponent places monsters higher than 2000 ATK, just keep them.

7) Finally, activate "Time Wizard of Tomorrow". So, here are two possible outcomes of coin flip:

  • If you have guessed right, you can inflict lethal damage.
  • If you have guessed wrong, you would have taken damage, had there not been Oracle and Number 43 without any protection done in #4 and #5. You see, when you would take damage, Oracle heals you with same amount. With Number 43 around, fortunately, you can inflict same amount of heal as damage for the FTK!

8) Congratulations, you win the game either way!

Just a little while ago, I used to FTK someone alongside Number 43 with addition in mind. Now, this time, I'll do it again but with subtraction. Nah, I'm joking, it will still be additive. Why don't you take a look?

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, send Number 13 and Makyura from the field to GY.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to have Primal Seed setup with you. Just don't banish Number 13 by accident and you will be good.

3) Revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into Number 43 with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch".

4) Activate "Reverse Trap" from your hand thanks to Makyura. Then, target "Gravity Lash" on Chaos Emperor. Normally, Chaos Emperor would lose its ATK equal to its DEF but "Reverse Trap" lets you increase its ATK instead.

5) Repeat "Gravity Lash" until the ATK of Chaos Emperor is higher than your opponent's LP. In that case, activate "Mystik Wok" and target on Chaos Emperor by choosing its ATK. May Number 43 give you life and your opponent a gruesome death.

deck_excerpt: Yuri couldn't have just conjured up the entire Predaplant lineup right away. He would have started small...
deck_description:
Yuri. Next to Zarc, he's one of the characters who was most explicitly making up new cards as he went along. But even he had to start somewhere. This is a suggestion as to what his deck might have looked like in Season 1 of Arc-V. It assumes he made the entire Invasion: Vengeance predaplant lineup early, but was otherwise limited to older cards to fill in gaps.

This is the best version of a Pure Charmer deck I can make at my current collection of cards etc. (I play paper)

A lot of the decks I see go too "all in" with the main deck and spread themselves too thin hitting every attribute at once. [I understand this since a lot of people use this site for Master Duel so no matches really] Most decks (yes some do) but most are only a few attributes and even multi attribute decks there are usually specific monsters in those that are problematic. So, that's what the side deck is for. The first duel will be a wash if your not typed up right but if you change out you might stand a chance. Let's be honest, this deck as a pure form is bad and if you play it you're not playing to win every game. Either way, if you do type it right you can disrupt your opponent by actually stealing monsters with your Charmers and further stealing with the link versions. 

I'm not sure if there's much else to talk about... the three extra Extra Deck monsters are just one's I had in my collection to fill the 15. Feel free to slim down or expand as you see fit. Nothing in here is set in stone per se but I definitely encourage you making it in a specific set of Attributes first. The most trouble I have when playing in my own casual eviroment is Earth, Dark, Light, and Wind so those are the main deck ones I chose. (Well, I picked wind more because they have the best Spiritual Art in my opinon Water is a close second) Also, yes, I'm on a very tight budget for Yu-Gi-Oh so most of the cards you see here are from the Structure deck or other easily accessed sources from one point in time. I did not go out of my way to buy anything for this deck except the link monsters because for some reason none of those were included in the structure deck???

Final notes, Unpossessed is KEY to this deck's survival. I only own 2 copies so I don't know if three is better or if it clogs you up. Your charmers being able to survive battle and steal will make your opponent waste monster/card destruction effects on your face down monsters even when you bait them with an attribute that can't steal (well, depends on the opponent) but if you have Awakening of the Possesed they have to hit that first etc etc...

If you're a fellow Charmers Enjoyer, Good Luck!

deck_excerpt: Surely the slow pace of both Ritual Monsters and Flip Monsters will cancel each other out, right?
deck_description:
Prediction Princess is a ritual archetype focused around turboing out their boss monsters Tarotrei and Tarotreith, both of which allow you to summon Flip monsters, and then flip them on your opponent's turn. Obvious flip monster targets include:

- Guard Dog - No special summons for the turn

- Whirlwind Weasel - No Spell/Trap activations for the turn (Note: Both WW and GD are lingering effects. If the effect resolves, even if they leave field the floodgate is in effect.)


Other useful ones include:

- Pot of the Forbidden: Has 4 effects, and you get to pick any of them. Draw 2, bounce all spell/traps back to hand, a Raigeki effect, or a Forceful Sentry effect.

- Deus X-Krawler: Unlike most Flip monsters, if Deus is flipped, as long as it remains on field, the effect remains. That effect being a negation of all monster effects activated on your opponent's field. This applies even if the monster leaves the field by any means (Vanquish Soul return-to-hand effects for instance).

Surely the slow pace of both Ritual Monsters and Flip Monsters will cancel each other out, right?

Greetings! In this deck, we will FTK the opponent with "Trickstar Black Catbat" featuring "Samsara Lotus" alongside a crafty setup. Before we start, check these options before/during the game and change them as shown, which matters later on:

 

- Self-Chain >>> On

- Card Position >>> Manual

- Activation Order Settings >>> On

 

(Now, let the show begin!)

 

Gameplan

1) When you Link Summon Saryuja, make sure at least two adjacent arrows ("Bottom-Left and Bottom" or "Bottom and Bottom-Right") Saryuja point to are free. Plan your summons with Panda accordingly and don't forget to play "Into the Void" in advance, which is needed to send Samsara to GY.

2) Place both Pendulum Monsters on Zones and try to perform a Pendulum Summon...

  • While doing so, place Lilybell on where Saryuja points to and reserve a spot next to Lilybell, which will be spared for "Supreme King Dragon". This is why you have to make sure at least two adjacent Main Monster Zones (MMZ) are free, explained in #1.
  • If there are still empty MMZ, fill them with any monster except Samsara but bring forth Wanghu as last one. The aim is to not destroy any monster by accident with Wanghu but don't forget to reserve a spot for Supreme.

3) Fusion Summon Supreme by using Bufolicula + Triantis as materials by activating Bufolicula. Then, place Supreme next to Lilybell and activate Supreme to copycat Lilybell...

  • If you don't have Supreme or fear the fact that Supreme might be banned one day, you need to Pendulum Summon another Lilybell. When you are done with Pendulum Summon, destroy both Pendulum Zones with "Twin Twisters", seen in "Side Deck". Reason behind is that Samsara can be Special Summoned at your End Phase in Attack Position, only if you don't control any Spell/Trap cards, which is what Bufolica somewhat does it anyways.

4) You have two Trickstar monsters. Yes, changing name with Supreme counts. So, Link Summon Catbat with these two and jump to End Phase.

5) If the button at the lower-right corner of the screen is either "ON" or "Auto", activate "Into the Void", which delivers Samsara to GY. Then, change these options in-game to not waste any time with manual labor...

  • Self-Chain >>> On
  • Card Position >>> Auto
  • Activation Order Settings >>> Off

6) Now, you can revive Samsara with a single button and Wanghu can destroy it in an instant. Since the only spot Samsara can go is where Catbat points to, you can deal 200 damage until your opponent is dead...

  • When the game is over, feel free to revert into your default options or keep them. It's up to your preferences.

7) Congratulations, you win the game!

deck_excerpt: "OMG yes I love Quem! I would die for Guiding Quem, the Virtuous. - YCS Champ Joshua Schmidt
deck_description:
"OMG yes I love Quem! I would die for Guiding Quem, the Virtuous. This support card is going to change my life and is going to be the best card ever!" - YCS Champ Joshua Schmidt

Okay, maybe he really didn't say that and it's just a copypasta constantly posted in his Youtube comments and Twitch streams, but you get the point - YCS Champ Joshua won by skillfully piloting Bystial Runick! And now, we can do the same in Masterduel since the latest pack makes all the important pieces in the strategy available!

Combining Bystial with Runick, another amazing advantage engine, you get an extremely competent meta strategy that will quickly outpace your opponents! Piloted correctly and methodically, Bystial Runick will win you games vs. the top decks of the metagame, especially since Bystial hard counters decks like Branded, Dragonlink and Labyrinth!
 
This deck may be straightforward, but it rewards good decision making since boards and gamestates are determined by the pilot's skill and resource management. If you're a player who likes a resource-based control-focused grindgame, Bystial Runick is the deck for you.
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
UPDATE - Chaos Ruler has been banned according to Masterduel's most recent banlist, so take it out of your Bystial Runick deck. Even though it's powerful, it isn't needed for the strategy.
 
As the name implies, Bystial Runick is mainly composed of the two archetypes. 

The BYSTIAL part of the deck actually just isn't Bystial, it represents the Albaz "synchro" cards as well such as Cartesia, Aluber, and of course, Quem! Bystials offer their level 6 bodies for Synchro summons, mostly for Baronne or Dis Pater. Combined with the Fusion monsters summoned by Runick spells (level 2 Hugin and level 4 Geri), level 6 and level 10 synchro monsters from your extra deck toolbox are easily accessible. Bystials also form a compact but effect resource loop when Branded Regained + Beast are on the field, forming an incredible amount of advatage for the pilot in both bodies on the field and cards in hand. Bystials are so incredibly powerful. Being a "D.D. Crow" for lights/darks, a giant 2500ATK body and free level 6 bodies for summon fodder is incredible! When your opponent is out of resources, the sheer amount of Bystials + level 10 synchro bosses can wait one turn on a full board to OTK your opponent - one of the few Runick variants to do so. 
 
RUNICK offers the main win condition of this deck by banishing your opponent's deck. Runick spells also break opponent's boards fairly well when played correctly in tandem with the other archetypes, especially Bystials. Runick offers solid defensive options, with Hugin protecting against destruction effects while Geri dissuades the opponent from attacking. Constantly drawing up to three cards per turn is pretty bonkers too, easily allowing the pilot to outpace the opponent with the amount of resources they have.
 
Duality is also included in this deck. The card offers Hugin (its target is Allvain) a way to dodge targeting negation like Imperm or Veiler. Duality can also turn a level 6 Bystial into a light tuner (its target is Malong). An added bonus is that when Malong reaches the GY, it can return a face-up card to the hand! Finally, Duality can recycle 1 light and 1 dark card in the GY for a draw, which additional recursion and resource advantage. The card isn't needed (you can save on 90 UR!) in this deck, but it greatly benefits the strategy. 
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The strategy of Bystial Runick is to control/banish your opponent's cards until they surrender or deck-out. In certain situations, you can also enter the battle phase and OTK your opponent. The ridiculous resource advantage and control options each archetype gives the duelist should win them the duel in most circumstances. An additional benefit to using a lot of Bystials is that is hardcounters various common strategies onf Masterduel ladder like Branded, Labyrinth and Tearlaments. 
 
There is no particular combo line that this strategy uses. Mostly, this deck just summons Hugin to start off with the Runick portion of the deck. The presence Hugin then allows the special summons of Spright monsters so you can full combo. Bystials are not particularly "needed," but if you draw into Lubellion, Magnamhut and Branded Regained, it grants you massive resources, interruptions and free bodies on the field. 
 
Normal summoning Quem to dump to GY Bystial Aluber is typically the opening play. Summoning Cartesia to fuse into Granguinol is also another line of play, since Granguinol can send Luluwalilith to summon Quem from deck, or it's level 8 body can be used as Synchro material for Chaos Angel. Typically, a level 6 Bystial + Cartesia/Quem (level 4 tuners) can make your level 10 Synchro of choice. 
 
The deck's endboard is varies, but the duelist may end on a mix of level 10 Synchro boss monsters (Typically Baronne), and with one or both of the Bystial continuous spell or traps. 
 
Since this is a toolbox control strategy, the use of each card is unique and situational - after Hugin -> Bystial combo, the duel is typically non-linear. Instead, the game is dependent on the pilot's decision-making, resource advantage skills and knowledge of the specific match-up. If played to it's best potential, this deck can defeat opponents going first and second, even through many interruptions. 
 
With the unique control each archetype offers and the draw 3-4+ every turn, your opponent should wither away while you snowball card advantage to victory. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Similarly to Sky Striker, this is a toolbox control resource deck. It has a high skill ceiling since it factors in a player's decision making, resource management and match-up knowledge. Practice makes perfect with the deck!
  • Duality isn't needed in this deck, but it provides a way for Hugin to dodge interruption (like an imperm or veiler), or for your Bystial to turn into a tuner + bounce (Malong).
  • Both Bystials and Runick form great body blockers to defend your lifepoints if it comes down to it.
  • Bystials are excellent when breaking boards, beating down small monsters and baiting interruption. You can enter battle phase to clear your opponent's board with 2500ATK beatsticks and continue your Runick plays during battlephase or main phase 2! 
  • This deck can generate so many bodies on board that it can easily OTK your opponent. If you feel your opponent cannot withstand your attack and they're out of resources, try to intentionally hold back from using Runick cards so you can enter the battle phase to finish them off!
  • Remember, if a card is on the Extra Monster Zone, you cannot summon the defensive Runick fusions Hugin and Geri! Summon your Fusion and Synchro monsters in the Main Monster Zones rather than the Extra Monster Zone!
  • Hugin's search effect for Runick Fountain isn't once per turn. If you can spare the cards, you can still search for Runick Fountain a second time! This makes Hugin ideal bait for your opponent's interruption. 
  • If your opponent Maxx "C,"'s you, stop summoning and don't take the maxx c challenge! It's not worth giving your opponent more resources when you're righting a resource war. You can simply summon with 1 monster and leave it at that, since you can always summon your Runick or Bystial monsters during your opponent's turn!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
I dunno about you guys, but drawing 4+ cards with Bystial Runick per turn is sooooo satisfying! Ending on a multiple interruption board with 6+ cards in hand makes you feel like the richest duelist ever! The Bystial Runick toolbox control gameplay is extremely fun and rewarding as well, since every game feels like winning a hard-fought battle utilizing a mastermind's tactician's decision making combined with a strategist's logistical mastery. Games tend to be long winded and grindy, with the win condition on both sides focused on resources rather than life points. 
 
The cool thing about Runick is that it's from the "first person view" so it feels like you're fighting alongside your monsters (kind of like when you summon allies in Skyrim)! Imagine that - you're now an integral main character of the Branded storyline. With your tactical decision making and careful management of battlefield resources, will you emerge victorious in your very own Branded saga? 

Now, I will leave you with the copypasta derived from the recent YCS Champ who piloted this deck to victory, Joshua Schmidt - "OMG yes I love Quem! I would die for Guiding Quem, the Virtuous. This support card is going to change my life and is going to be the best card ever!"
 
GLHF Duelists!

Hey there! It's well-known that "Soul-Absorbing Bone Tower" is associated with Mill decks but did you know you can also win alongside "Jackpot 7" on the very first turn? Well, now you do, so keep reading.

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, activate "Double Summon" and place a plant to opposing side with "Black Garden", right above one of Extra Monster Zone (EMZ).

2) After Link Summoning Saryuja, Special Summon "Bone Tower", right below one of EMZ. Then, Normal Summon "Meiru", thanks to "Double Summon".

3) Link Summon "Reprodocus" by using Saryuja and any monster but Tower/Meiru as materials, just above where "Bone Tower" is. Next, change the Attribute of "Bone Tower" to anything but LIGHT or DARK to not let Tower being negated by Meiru. Then, pass Tower to opposing side with "Mystic Box" by replacing the plant you have placed with "Black Garden".

4) After activating "Zombie World" while having all three "Jackpot 7" cards in your deck, Special Summon Booster. By doing so, you can start milling your deck with Tower to trigger all three "Jackpot 7" cards and win the duel.

5) To repeat the process explained in #4, you need to return Booster to your hand with Birdman. Since Birdman is DARK monster, you can return Booster (cost) but you can't Special Summon Birdman (effect) due to Meiru. Therefore, Special Summoning Booster and returning it with Birdman is a continuous manual loop, leading to your victory.

deck_excerpt: Blast Asmodian FTK ft. Primal Seed
deck_description:
Hello there! This deck is bread and butter for learning chains while burning your opponent to death with "Blast Asmodian". Let me explain.

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, try discarding all three "Blast Asmodian" cards with Ravenous and Dugares but you have to discard at least two via Ravenous.

2) After you have Link Summoned Saryuja, Special Summon "Blast Asmodian" with it. Then, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup Primal Seed loop, which is used for finding combo pieces from Banish Zone (BZ).

3) Revive other two "Blast Asmodian" with "Monster Reborn". If there are no board space for them, open up with "Self-Mummification".

4) So, there are four ways to FTK your opponent with "Blast Asmodian" but the basis is starting a chain with Quick-Play spells. You have to repeat what was explained below until they are dead...

  • After playing "Primal Seed" to find something, play "Pot of Acquisitiveness", if you haven't already. You can only play it once, though.
  • After playing "Primal Seed" to find something, play "Reload" as many times as possible. Also, don't worry, you won't lose "Primal Seed" during the shuffle process because shuffling is going to happen first.
  • After playing "Primal Seed" to find something, if you have a monster as excess coming from "Monster Reborn", play "Self-Mummification".
  • While "Blast Asmodian" cards are triggering, you can make a follow-up by playing any Quick-Play spell you have, which also ignites another series of burn coming from "Blast Asmodian" cards.

deck_excerpt: C1 OTK ft. Panda+Arcana Force+Numeron Network
deck_description:
Good day to you! If you are looking at this deck, that means you must be interested in Numeron decks. Generally speaking, C1 is mostly used as emergency rather than burst, where you can banish all monsters and burst damage is low, if only XYZ s banished were Numerons. What if I told you that burst damage can go high only with your cards, ranging up to 10k, and you can do all in one turn thanks to Panda and Arcana? If you are still curious, keep reading.

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have 3 x Level 1 dudes in your GY, Link Summon Saryuja. Then, play first "Tri-Wight" to revive them and overlay into "Number 1" by using 3 x Level 1 dudes as materials.

2) Special Summon Gale with Saryuja. Activate Gale twice by paying 6000 LP in total to send "Neo Galaxy-Eyes" XYZ monsters to GY. Then, overlay into C1 via "Number 1".

3) C1 was sent to Banish Zone (BZ), ready to blow up next turn. Fuel C1 with explosives by sending "Number 1" and "Neo Galaxy-Eyes" to BZ with "Soul Release".

4) After placing "Light Barrier", activate second "Tri-Wight". Then, reveal Arcana to bring forth "Angel O1", which allows you to Tribute Summon Arcana. When Arcana hits the board, choose the outcome as heads to skip your opponent's turn.

5) Activate "Numeron Network" and end your turn. To skip your opponent's turn, send the remaining Level 1 dudes to GY. On your Standby Phase of next turn, activate C1 to deal 4500 + 4500 + 1000 = 10000 damage in total for the OTK...

  • Technically, the XYZ monster with highest ATK value is "Galaxy Destroyer" with 5000 ATK, seen in "Side Deck". However, they are UR to craft and can be only found in "Legacy Pack". Since I don't have them, I had to cut 1 x Upstart Goblin and replace XYZ fellas with "Neo Galaxy-Eyes" monsters, which are SR. If you have at least 2 x Galaxy Destroyer cards, definitely add them alongside 1 x Upstart Goblin instead.

I'm going to try to churn out these Level 9 EARTH monsters because I need the euphoria of Special Summoning Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from the Deck with World Legacy Monstrosity. The Level 9 monster we are looking at this time is Naturia Leodrake which is a Level 9 EARTH Beast Non-Effect Synchro Monster that requires an EARTH Tuner and 1 or more non-Tuner EARTH monsters. I don’t think I have seen anyone even try to Summon Leodrake. First of all, it has no effect. Second of all, it is not exactly a generic Synchro Monster. Thankfully, the Naturia support from DABL exists along with Fusion Armament. Fusion Armament reveals a Fusion Monster in Extra Deck and Special Summons 1 of the monsters listed on that monster as Fusion Material from Extra Deck or GY, but it cannot attack and has its effects negated until the end of your opponent’s turn. Naturia Exterio mentions both Naturia Beast and Naturia Barkion as Fusion Material, meaning that you can get one of them out for a Level 5 or 6 EARTH monster to help you get to Leodrake. So, then you would need a Level 3 or Level 4 EARTH Tuner to go with one of them to make Leodrake. Naturia Camellia is a Level 4 EARTH Tuner which can be used with Naturia Beast to make Leodrake. So, we just need to get both of them on field and Synchro with them. Naturia Mole Cricket can Tribute itself to Summon a Naturia from Deck and can Special Summon itself from GY if a Naturia is Special Summoned from Extra Deck. Fusion Armament, as it is a “Fusion” Spell Card, can be searched by Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. So this culminates into a 2-card combo of Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and Naturia Mole Cricket. Normal Scorpio and discard Mole Cricket to get Cobra from Deck. Cobra adds Fusion Armament and you activate it revealing Exterio to get Naturia Beast from Extra Deck. Mole Cricket triggers to Summon itself from GY. Tribute Mole Cricket for Camellia from Deck. Camellia triggers on Summon to send a Naturia card from Deck to GY. Send Naturia Sacred Tree which is a mandatory trigger if sent to GY to search a Naturia card. Add Naturia Blessing from Deck to hand. Synchro Camellia and Beast into Leodrake. Activate Blessing to Special Summon Camellia from GY. Synchro Camellia and Scorpio into Shooting Riser Dragon. Shooting Riser triggers on Special Summon to send Shaddoll Beast from Deck to GY to make itself a Level 2 monster. Tune Shooting Riser and Cobra into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which adds World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon and you know the rest. I would say that this Deck is really cool, and it is really nice that it is just a 2-card combo to get to a Level 9 and Monstrosity. However, I wouldn’t be making Leodrake of course as I would rather make something that can get Bibliomuse out of the Deck if targeted with Monstrosity. Also, this Deck has a lot of garnets. Granted, you don’t need to technically search Fusion Armament or Naturia Blessing or send Naturia Sacred Tree if you already drew Armament or Blessing, but you do have to ensure that you have Cobra, Shaddoll Beast, and Camellia in Deck to search/Summon/send them. Either way, it’s a really cool Deck.

For the Main Deck Monsters: For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY face-down if she was Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, she gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on the field, you can add a Level 9 monster from your Deck to your hand with a different Type and Attribute than this card. 2 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju which we are playing as a Level 9 we can get off of targeting Leodrake with Monstrosity. 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag which is a Level 9 we can easily Summon. It can Special Summon itself from hand if there is a monster in the EMZ and it is aslo a Level 9 we can get off of Monstrosity. 1 Shaddoll Beast to send off of Shooting Riser Dragon for Level modulation and it is also a Flip Monster. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Scorpio discards a monster on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. Cobra adds a Fusion or Polymerization Spell from Deck to hand if Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster once per Duel. 2 Lonefire Blossom which Tributes a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 2 Naturia Camellia which we are only using for its first effect and because it is a Level 4 EARTH Tuner we can easily access. On Normal or Special Summon, it sends a Naturia card from Deck to GY. 3 Naturia Mole Cricket which can Tribute itself as a Quick Effect to Special Summon a Naturia from Deck or 2 Naturia if your opponent controls the monster with the highest ATK on the field. Also, if you Special Summon a Naturia monster from your Extra Deck, you can Special Summon it from GY.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction. It Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can also banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 1 Instant Fusion and 1 Fusion Armament. 2 World Legacy Monstrosity  which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than that monster but with different names. 2 Naturia Blessing which we are only using to Special Summon a Naturia from hand or GY. 1 Naturia Sacred Tree which we are only using to search a Naturia card as a mandatory effect if sent to GY. 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment. 1 Naturia Exterio. 1 Master of Ham. 1 Naturia Leodrake. 1 Shooting Riser Dragon. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. 1 Naturia Beast. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand if sent to GY. 1 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

deck_excerpt: Taking a look at Hyper Psychic Blaster
deck_description:
If anything, the new Gusto support from DAMA, while it is really good for the Deck, doesn’t really help the Deck when the Deck’s biggest problem is the fact that their floaters miss timing. However, it really does help out the Synchro aspect of the Deck. Today’s Level 9 monster that we are looking at is Hyper Psychic Blaster which is a Level 9 EARTH Psychic Synchro Monster that requires 1 Tuner and 1 or more non-Tuner Psychic monsters as Synchro Material. It inflicts piercing damage and the rest of its effect is really worded weirdly but the TLDR of it is that at the end of the damage step, if it attacked a Defense Position monster with DEF lower than its ATK, you gain Life Points equal to the difference. That being, its current DEF if it’s still on the field or original DEF if it is no longer on the field. I’ve actually played with this card a bunch in Duel Links I think back when the card pack with Dimensional Prison released since it had the neo-Sayer cards like Psychic Wheeleder and Psychic Tracker which were good for Synchro Summoning the 3-axis Synchros and the like at that time, especially with cards like Overdrive Teleporter. So why are we talking about Gustos all of a sudden? Well, with their new card in Tailwind of Gusto, it makes getting out Hyper Psychic Blaster comically easy. Do the Gusto cards do anything outside of that in this Deck? Not really. Most of their good cards either require you to play more Gusto names to make better use of them or they WIND-lock you for the rest of the turn which we can’t really work with. I mean what else would you want me to play to make Hyper Psychic Blaster? Make P.U.N.K. JAM Dragon Drive and activate Emergency Teleport to get a Dimensional Allotrope Varis from Deck? That actually doesn’t sound too bad, but I would much rather save P.U.N.K. for when I attempt to make a Prediction Princess Deck focusing on Overmind Archfiend, who is one of the more infuriatingly bad neo-Sayer cards to be released. We have a few 3-card combos to get us where we need to go, but the two at the top of my head are Gusto Vedir + Tailwind of Gusto + World Legacy Monstrosity and Foolish Burial Goods + Gusto Griffin + World Legacy Monstrosity. Going with the first combo, Normal Summon Vedir, equip it with Tailwind, use Tailwind to Special Summon Windaar, Sage of Gusto from Deck, Synchro into Hyper Psychic Blaster, and activate Monstrosity. Second combo: activate Foolish Burial Goods to send Tailwind of Gusto from Deck to GY, activate Tailwind in GY to discard Griffin and add another Tailwind from Deck to hand, trigger Griffin to get Vedir from Deck, equip it with Tailwind, use Tailwind to get Windaar from Deck, Synchro into Hyper Psychic Blaster, and activate Monstrosity. Is it good? Not really. If anything, Synchroing for something other than Hyper Psychic Blaster would be much more worthwhile, especially since it gets you Bibliomuse whereas Hyper Psychic Blaster cannot as it is EARTH. But we are playing other Level 9 Synchros, so you do have the choice. It’s a simple combo, but it works.

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY face-down if she was Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, she gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on the field, you can add a Level 9 monster from your Deck to your hand with a different Type and Attribute than this card. 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag which is a Level 9 we can easily Summon. It can Special Summon itself from hand if there is a monster in the EMZ and you can target a monster in the EMZ and equip it to itself. Then, if it destroys a monster by battle, it can Special Summon a monster that is equipped to it. 1 Frodi, Generaider Boss of Swords which is just a WIND Level 9 monster. Its effect does not matter. 1 Mariamne, the True Dracophoenix which is another WIND Level 9. You can destroy 2 monsters from hand and/or field including a WIND monster to Special Summon her from your hand. This technically can trigger some of your cards like Gusto Griffin and it can also act as your Level 9 monster on field for Monstrosity to target if you really want. The reason why we are playing Frodi and Mariamne is because we need WIND monsters to discard for Tailwind of Gusto. We are only playing a few Gustos and having more WINDS to be able to discard for Tailwind’s GY effect really does help, especially since you can also use Frodi and Mariamne as Monstrosity targets. For the Gustos: 1 Windaar, Sage of Gusto, 3 Gusto Vedir, and 3 Gusto Griffin. Windaar is just a Level 6 Gusto we need to Special Summon from Deck off of Tailwind. Vedir can Special Summon itself if a face-up Gusto monster on the field is destroyed by battle or card effect and it can send a Gusto from Deck to GY to optionally Special Summon a Gusto from hand. But, we are realistically just using it as a Level 3 non-Psychic Gusto monster to equip Tailwind to in order to get Windaar from Deck to Synchro into Hyper Psychic Blaster. If anything, you could use its effect to dump a Gusto from Deck to send a copy of Kamui, Hope of Gusto from Deck as it is a Flip Monster if you want to be cute, but the more important theory behind this effect is that you can Special Summon a Gusto from hand like Windaar. Tailwind only Special Summons from Deck, so if you happen to draw Windaar, you can still get him onto the field from hand with Vedir. Griffin can Special Summon a Gusto from Deck if it is sent from hand or GY. And this effect is a hard once per turn. Out of nowhere, we just have a Gusto with an “If” clause that is hard once per turn which is so strange to me. But it can be discarded for Tailwind’s effect from GY to get you a Gusto from Deck. 

For the Spell/Traps: 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can also banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which only Ritual Summons Prediction Princess Tarotrei and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to add a Prediction Princess monster from Deck to hand. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites. 3 Foolish Burial Goods. 3 Tailwind of Gusto which is an Equip Spell that only equips to a Gusto monster, making it unable to be destroyed by your opponent’s card effects. You can banish it from GY and discard a WIND monster to add a Gusto Spell/Trap (including itself) from Deck to hand. And while it is equipped to a monster, if the monster is Level/Rank 4 or lower, you can Special Summon a Gusto with a different Type than the equipped monster from Deck or if the monster is Level/Rank 5 or higher, you can Special Summon a Level 1 Tuner from Deck. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than that monster but with different names. And 3 Pot of Prosperity. 

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys and 1 Cloudcastle as our alternate Level 9 Synchro options. 1 Hyper Psychic Blaster. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, 3 Evenly Matched, and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

deck_excerpt: A Gate Guardian deck designed to be as competitive as possible for Masterduel. Still a casual deck though!
deck_description:
I've tried to make Gate Guardian as viable as possible for Masteduel ladder, but try as I might, the deck is still casual. It may steal a game or two (especially if the opponent doesn't read cards) but usually it gets outclassed and beaten.

I'm not going to make an in-depth guide for this deck since it's really basic to play and it's fairly weak. Basically, try to summon Gate Guardians Combined by sending to GY or placing on field Suijin, Kazejin and Sanga. From there, you try to beat your opponent down with giant boss monsters that always float backwards to their more basic forms. Once you got the big three in rotation in the banished pile, GY and field, you have a good grind game to beat your opponent down with.

There are no supplemental engines with this version of the deck, so I tried to stuff in as many staples as possible so the deck can play in it's "pure" form.

GLHF Duelists, and Happy New Year! May we have another amazing year of Yugioh!

Good day to you! Everything is burning up with "Goka, the Pyre of Malice". So, why not fuel it more with Number 43?

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to have Primal Seed setup ready.

2) Special Summon Goka, either with "Monster Reborn" if discarded by Dugares/Ravenous or with Saryuja.

3) If Number 13 was sent to GY beforehand, revive it with "Monster Reborn" and get rid of Saryuja with "Mystik Wok". Otherwise, XYZ Summon Number 13 and get rid of it with "Mystik Wok" first. Then, overlay into Number 43 with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch" by using Number 13 as material and place Number 43 on Extra Monster Zone (EMZ).

4) If you have done everything right, there should be three free Main Monster Zones (MMZ), which will be refilled via "Tri-Wight". Otherwise, spare with "Mystik Wok". After playing "Temple >>> Transplant" combo and choosing FIRE as Attribute, you can tribute these three Level 1 dudes with Goka to boost its ATK.

5) When the ATK of Goka is higher than your opponent's LP, activate "Mystik Wok" on Goka and choose its ATK. By gaining LP with respect to its ATK, Number 43 can generate a big blast to kill your opponent.

deck_excerpt: Amazoness, Queen, Princess, Secret Arts, Golden Whip, Sliver Sword, Baby Tiger, Kaiju, Spiritualist
deck_description:
Intro

Man it has been a long while since I uploaded another Amazoness Deck well this is mine that I have in rl and the goal in mind was to make a casual deck I wanted the causal deck to be at least good  to have fun with and try to play the game so, this is the break down I had for this deck I have switch from this deck just being a fusion and xyz deck I have added in links and to be honest I am surprised that I didn't wanted link monsters before but I have some here that I like a lot and still miss that Isoldee is banned but I am not to surprised that it's banned. Also, there will be a text of what is in the deck for those who just want to skip to the list.

The Breakdown 

For the main monsters I have most of the Amazoness monsters that you will see a lot of people play 1x Queen, 3x Princess, 3x War Chief, 2x of each one Sliver and Gold, 2x Spiritualist, 1x Baby Tiger. These are the monsters you will see most decks have and with good reason since you Princess and War Chief you have these two being your main searchers thoughout the deck this can be for anything from Monsters, Spells and Traps form the deck to either the hand or field, Spiritualist to bring back a trap or spell and get a fusion card ready, these cards not being part of the Amazoness archetype aka normal poly and fusion sub. From the older support I have Swords Woman still a good effect after all this time, Paladin and Sage you could take these two out but I would just use them for XYZ summon more than anything else but Sage effect could still be good? For the XYZ monster #41 I think is a good monster that you can XYZ summon into but you could use a different monster for here either like Tornado Dragon, Castel Sky Blaster etc.

I added in two Kaiju monsters and there spell card interrupted Kaiju Slumber I feel like you need a "modern dark hole" to get ride of some monsters that could be a pain in the ass to deal with and well from what I seen Kaiju's are a good form of monster removal if you still need your normal summon but you could switch these cards out for something like Lava Golem, Ra Sphere Mode, or Nibiru.  For the hand traps I feel like Ash is always good to have in  most decks since the effects are generic that they work for the next one I think you could switch out Ghost Bell for either something like D.D Crow,  Skull Meister, or Bystial Druiswurm but this can change since Druiswurm depending on format for me I like Ghost Bell while it is hard once pre turn I do like how it stops effects from the grave effects beside called by the grave you could switch out Ghost Bell for something else.

For the Goblindbergh I would say that I only use this as a way to have a monster form of "double summon" I say it in this way is because if you read the effect of the card you can only select one level 4 monster and lower and depending on what you get with this opening hand you could use it in that way after you have used your normal summons for example lets say I have 5 cards in my hand Amazoness Village,  Spiritualist,  Goblindbergh, Warchief and Princess  and how I would use this card is the following after this.

If your going 2nd

1. play village

2. activate Spiritualist, bounce back village when Spiritualist, search for either poly or sub fusion

3. activate village, then summon warchief and place a trap card down and now you have two monsters down

4. now either you can go in fusion monsters or use Goblin card summon it and then you could bring out Princess use its effects to search for another card

5. then after all of that you could use  Princess effect discard Goblin and then summon out Queen.

This is one example of how you could use this card as an opening hand while its not perfect but its an idea or so.

Main Deck:

Amazoness Queen x1

Amazoness Golden Whip Master x2

Amazoness War Chief x3

Amazoness Paladin x1

Amazoness Swords Woman x1

Amazoness Sage x1

Extra Deck:

Amazoness Empress x2

Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder x1

Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir x1

With the upcoming Jan 2024 banlist in MD, Speedroid TT is going to unlimited, which opens up this rank 3 XYZ spam deck up for fun against the currently weakened meta. This deck loses to droplet, super poly, dark ruler and the likes of very powerful spell/trap board breakers...as most decks do...but can play thru some interuption and going 2nd, can go into Zeus effectively and on main phase 2, combo off. 

Optimally, going 1st, you should end on DPE, I:P, Naturia Beast, Verte and UDF. On turn 2, main phase 1, turn I:P and Verte into Avramax or if you need more disruption to your opponents board...go into Unicorn and watch a quick surrender, unless they don't read that Naturia Beast isn't once per turn or that Avramax is untargetable, can't be destroyed and has to be attacked into. 

Overall a fun deck, getting a slight power boost. Plenty of ways to play and certain cards like Rescue Cat don't have to be played or in place of other options. I like running sekka's light as not many decks can do that...sure not playing called by the grave hurts when facing a Maxx C, but sometimes you can come close to decking the opponent out if they don't have a way to stop your numerous special summons this deck can muster.

Greetings! You might have heard of infamous Cyber-Stein, where it was banned in MD about 6-7 months ago. It's because you can cheat out Fusion Monsters as many times as you can with Telekinetic Charging Cell and Brain Research Lab applied, provided you have changed the Type of Cyber-Stein to Psychic via Reprodocus and alike, which was pretty easy to do and was abused in Lyrilusc - Independent Nightingale FTK decks. Now, imagine Cyber-Stein with more balanced version as Flip Monster. This is where "Summoner of Illusions" comes in and I had to pick this card because no way I'll spend 30 SR and 30 UR, just to craft Fusion Materials for Dragoon, namely Dogma and Plasma. Anyways, with the background history given, we can start analyzing how to FTK with Dragoon.

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, plant a flower to opposing side with "Black Garden", if you go first. Then, destroy "Black Garden" with Ravenous and replace the rose with Jizukiru.

2) You need to activate "Chain Summoning" to gain two more Normal Summons. Fortunately, you can decide how to do...

  • Any Spell >>> Ravenous to destroy Garden >>> CS (This should be your primary method.)
  • Integrator >>> Stardust >>> CS (Done in this video.)
  • Librarian >>> Quick-Play Spell >>> CS
  • Librarian >>> Formula/Martial/Accel >>> CS

3) Set your opponent's LP to 3000 with Linewalker. Then, set "Summoner of Illusions" and flip it with "Book of Taiyou" to activate Illusions. Feel free to tribute any monster, including Illusions.

4) You have cheated out Dragoon without using Fusion Materials. Simply activate Dragoon and target Jizukiru to win the game! Be mindful of any ATK modifications, which is why we had to destroy "Black Garden".

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Destiny End Dragoon" can be found within "Shrouded Heroes" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 600 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

I won a local tournament with this deck. Brewed it myself. I figured the Runick cards would work well as extenders/tech cards and didnt need fountain. The Generaider core is consistant and hits really hard. It allows for strong boards and combos building Rank 9 XYZ monsters with strong effects. It has fantastic grind game and hardly bricks. The Draconnet line is a 1 card combo that gets Ib, this searches "World Legacy Mostrosity", this paired with a Runick card to summon Geri makes "Shenshen" which acts as a perfect bridge for "Monstrosity". "Munin" prevents "Justicia" from bricking your hand, allowing it to function as a Normal Summon. Each "Runick" spell is quite strong doubling as a form of interaction to stop your opponent or play through their board. Though they mainly serve as extenders. "Sauravis" is a fantastic tech card. Negating an effect that targets your monster is stupid strong. In the comp I shut down many "vailer" 's and "Imperm." 's with it. It basicaly forces your opponent to have "Nib." or "Ash" to stop your combo. Even still "Nib." isn't always useful against this Deck. "Sauravis" also helps play through boards, shutting down "S:P Little Knight", and many other meta stratagies that use targeting effects.

Over all, this deck is quite strong, handles itself very well against the current meta.
