deck_excerpt: Stealth Union making me want to unionize
deck_description:
I have beef with Vehicroid. Why did Konami think that the best way of excluding Speedroids from their search/summon targets being that you would be limited to non-WIND "roid" monsters? It's baffling to me that they decided to go this route because Vehicroids literally have WIND monsters in their archetype, 2 of them being their best Main Deck monsters. Dragonroid discards itself from hand to either search a non-WIND roid monster or give you a Magical Meltdown or Branded Lost-type Continuous Effect for the rest of the turn for your Fusion Summons. And it discarding itself puts a Machine in GY for Mixeroid, the other incredible WIND Vehicroid. It tributs a Machine to Special Summon a non-WIND roid from Deck and you can halve your Life Points and banish it and any number of Machine monsters from your GY to Special Summon a roid Fusion Monster with the same Level as the number of Machine monsters you banished to activate this effect, ignoring its Summoning Conditions and destroying it during the End Phase. Dear lord, I wish that I could play Dragonroid to search for Mixeroid in this Deck, but I can't because of that restriction. Just put "except a "Speedroid" monster" like an "except "Frog the Jam"" type of situation. Eitherway, the Level 9 monster we are taking a look at today is Super Vehicroid - Stealth Union which is a Level 9 EARTH Machine Fusion Monster that requires Truckroid, Expressroid, Drillroid, and Stealthroid as Fusion Material and it has an atrociously bad effect. There is no way that I am hard-summoning this card with its actual Fusion Materials, so the only other option would be to use Mixeroid's GY effect to banish it and 8 other Machines from GY to cheat Stealth Union out from the Extra Deck. Off the top of my mind, the Deck that puts a lot of Machines into the GY is Superheavy Samurai, so that is what we are using to dump Machines into GY for Mixeroid's effect. And an added bonus of using Superheavy Samurai to do this is that you can make Ib the World Chalice Justiciar as well to search for World Legacy Monstrosity, so that means you don't have to hard draw it. I actually had the idea for this Deck a couple of months ago, but since Ib wasn't unbanned at the time, you were limited to like a 4 or 5-card combo to get Stealth Union out onto the field and have Monstrosity to go through with your Prediction Princess combo. Since that was a flop, I thought about using Girsu, the Orcust Mekk-Knight to Summon a World Legacy Token to your opponent's field and use Super Vehicroid - Mobile Base to target that and get Mixeroid out from the Deck. Or maybe even do some kind of Geonator Transverser combo to get a monster with over 3600 onto your opponent's field for Mobile Base to get Stealth Union straight from the Extra Deck then. But that was too complicated, so I went back to my original idea which proved to be much better. The combo that ended up working for me is Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi, a Level 1 or Level 4 non-Tuner Superheavy Samurai monster, and Mixeroid. Let's say that our Level 1 or 4 non-Tuner SHS is Superheavy Samurai Soulhorns. Scale Wakaushi and use its Pend Effect to Scale Superheavy Samurai Monk Big Benkei from Deck and Summon Wakaushi from Scale. Benkei's Pend Effect adds Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster from Deck. Equip Soulhorns and Soulgaia Booster to Wakaushi and Special Summon both of them. Synchro Soulhorns and Wakaushi into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar and use her effect to search for World Legacy Monstrosity. Normal Summon Mixeroid and use its effect to tribute itself for Steamroid from Deck. Xyz Soulgaia Booster and Steamroid into Gear Gigant X which detaches 1 and adds Superheavy Samurai Soulpiercer from Deck to hand. Pendulum Summon Soulpiercer and Synchro it with Ib to make Superheavy Samurai Beast Kyubi. Soulpiercer's GY effect adds Superheavy Samurai Bike from Deck. Send Bike to GY to add another Soulpiercer from Deck to hand. Equip Soulpiercer to SHS Beast Kyubi. Link SHS Beast Kyubi and Gear Gigant into Sky Striker Ace - Camellia. Soulpiercer adds a Wakaushi from Deck to hand. Link Camellia into Sky Strike Ace - Kagari. We now count our Machines in GY: 1 Superheavy Samurai Soulhorns, 1 Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster, 2 Superheavy Samurai Soulpiercer, 1 Superheavy Samurai Motorbike, 1 Superheavy Samurai Beast Kyubi, 1 Mixeroid, 1 Steamroid, 1 Gear Gigant X, and 1 Sky Striker Ace - Camellia. That's 10 Machine monsters, so we can now banish Miceroid and 8 other Machines from GY to Special Summon Super Vehicroid - Stealth Union from Extra Deck ignoring it Summoning Conditions. Activate Monstrosity targeting Stealth Union and Special Summon 2 Level 9's with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck but with different names. We are playing Winged Kuriboh LV9, Big Whale, and Steelswarm Longhorn for targets. Could there have been alternative plays we could've done in that combo to perhaps end something else in addition to our Prediction Princess plays? Yes, you could've searched Superheavy Samurai Stealthy off of Motorbike and Special Summon it, Linking it and Gear Gigant into Camellia which keeps Kyubi on our field for another Level 9 on field to perhaps go for a Rank 9 play in Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows as a part of our endboard. We could've Summoned Cloudcastle instead of Kyubi which is a Level 9 target that gets Bibliomuse from Deck with Monstrosity, meaning that you could go into it instead of making Stealth Union. I hate this Deck. Get it away from me. I never want to look at a Vehicroid monster again. 

Before I get into the monsters, I want to talk about the Level 9 Monstrosity targets I am playing in this Deck: Winged Kuriboh LV9, Big Whale, and Steelswarm Longhorn. Winged Kuriboh LV9 isn't too bad of a Level 9 monster to build a Prediction Princess Deck around. I already have a Winged Kuriboh Prediction Princess Decklist I am planning to put up, but I am just tweaking at it a bit right now. Big Whale has an effect on Tribute Summon. We are never going to be using that effect, nor are we using it for anything else. Big Whale doesn't have an archetype surrounding it, and the generic Fish support doesn't do enough for me to contemplate making a Big Whale Prediction Princess Deck. If I wanted to make a Fish-Type Prediction Princess Deck, I'd go with Super Ancient Deepsea King Coelacanth which is just a better enabler for you to go into both Ib and Synchro 9's, multiple of them for that fact. As for Longhorn, Steelswarm is a Tribute Summon archetype. I am not about that at all, especially since Iswarm and Steelswarm don't have searchers. But the good news is that you can play Steelswarm Longhorn in Dark World Prediction Princess since Lucent, Netherlord of Dark World can get it straight from Deck. You just can't play the Archfiend Palabyrinth stuff since Longhorn isn't an Archfiend, but it still works to a degree in place of Annihilator Archfiend. 

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field dace-up or face-down and can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself from the GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and it searches for a Level 9 with a different Type and Attribute than itself if destroyed on field. 1 Winged Kuriboh LV9, 1 Big Whale, and 1 Steelswarm Longhorn. For the Superheavy Samurai monsters: 2 Superheavy Samurai Monk Big Benkei, 3 Superheavy Samurai Prodigy Wakaushi, 1 Superheavy Samurai Soulgaia Booster, 3 Superheavy Samurai Soulpiercer, 1 Superheavy Samurai Soulhorns, 3 Superheavy Samurai Motorbike, and 3 Superheavy Samurai Stealthy. We are using Monk Benkei only for its Pendulum Effect which is if you control a SHS monster, you can add a SHS Soul monster from Deck to hand. We are always using this effect to get something like Soulgaia Booster or Soulpiercer if we need a Level 4 non-Tuner for our combo or getting Soulhorns if we need a Level 1 non-Tuner. Wakaushi’s Pend Effect is that if you have no Spell/Traps in your GY, you can place a SHS Pend Monster except itself from Deck in your Pend Zone and Special Summon Wakaushi from its scale. And the only one of its monster effects that we are using is Wakaushi being able to scale itself from face-up Extra Deck if it is used as Synchro Material and sent there. Soulgaia Booster targets a SHS monster you control and equips itself from hand or field to that monster, and if it is equipped to a monster by its own effect, you can Special Summon it. Its other effects are not exactly relevant as we are just using this card as a Level 4 non-Tuner we are able to Summon. Soulpiercer also targets a SHS you control to equip itself from hand or field to that monster, and if it is sent from field to GY, you can add a SHS monster from Deck to hand other than itself. This effect is not once per turn. Soulhorns also targets a SHS you control and equips itself from hand or field to it, and while it is equipped by its own effect, you can Special Summon it. Motorbike can discard itself if you have no Spell/Traps in GY to add a Superheavy Samurai monster from Deck to hand except itself. It’s other effect allows you to target a Machine you control to increase its Level by 2, but we aren’t exactly Synchro comboing like you would normally in SHS, so this isn’t relevant. Stealthy is an inherent Special Summon from hand if you have no Spell/Traps in your GY once per turn. And since it is a Level 1 monster, it can also meet your Level 1 non-Tuner requirement. Also, if you have no Spell/Traps in GY, you can Quick Effect Tribute it to target a Spell/Trap in your opponent’s GY and set it to your field but banish it when it leaves the field. This effect will rarely come up, but supposedly if your opponent Imperms you and you already have a Level 1 non-Tuner other than Stealthy in rotation, you can use this to get another piece of interruption for yourself. 3 Gizmek Makami, the Ferocious Fanged Fortress which you would usually Pendulum Summon in this Deck if you really need to use its effect. On Normal or Special Summon, you can discard a card to search for a monster whose ATK equals its DEF except Makami which gets you Bibliomuse. 3 Mixeroid. 1 Steamroid and 1 Drillroid just as targets to Summon from Deck with Mixeroid.

.For Spell/Traps:3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction, 1 World Legacy Monstrosity, and 1 World Legacy Succession. Underworld Ritual can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. Monstrosity can either Special Summon a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 you control and Special Summon 2 Level 9’s from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than it but with different names. Succession Special Summons a monster from GY to your zone a Link Monster points to.

Extra Deck: 1 Super Vehicroid - Stealth Union. 1 Cloudcastle. 1 Superheavy Samurai Beast Kyubi. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. 2 Herald of the Arc Light. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Gear Gigant X. 1 Sky Striker Ace - Camellia. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, 1 Gravity Controller, and 1 Sky Striker Ace - Kagari.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 2 Dinowrestler Pankratops, 3 Fantasical Dragon Phantazmay, and 3 Effect Veiler.

Description:
Magistus has been a deck that hasn't seen any competitive play outside of small engines in pre-existing strategies. This attempts to use more Magistus cards combined with unforseen interactions to elevate the floor of the magistus deck. This version of the list is able to steal games against the top of the meta of TCG, which is a position that Magistus has never been in.

Of course, this isn't a pure build that some of you may have liked to see (with Rilliona + Magistus spells). Currently, all the magistus spells have little effective use and/or require to much setup to be anywhere close to valuable. In the future, we may get support (OCGStories) that make Rilliona easier to slot in, but I strive to make the baseline Magistus deck as strong as possible, which brings us to this decklist here. There is a lot of room for customization in this list, so feel free to tinker as you see fit.

Card List:

Hand-Traps/Board Breakers:

3x Fenrir

3x Ash Blossom

2x Droll and Lock Bird

1x Effect Veiler

1x Called by the Grave

3x Infinite Impermanece

Note: The Ratios for Droll/Veiler are due to the ability of witch to search them out. In a lot of hands, you will have more then enough for the combo (especially without opp interaction), so you can search these for added disruption.

 

Engine:

3x Endymion

3x Imesty

3x Zoroa

1x Witch of the Black Forest

1x Maximus

2x Nadir Servant

3x King's Sarcophagus

Note: Ratios for Nadir/Maximus is due to the prevelance of Droll in the format and the general value of Maximus in the hand. Maximus is a very good extender as another body and doesn't lose as hard to droll if hard drawn. Since we already run Zombie Vampire as a way to each of our engines, I didn't personally find value in maxing out Nadir, however these ratios are customizable to yourself.

Extenders:

2x Magicians' Souls

1x Nefarious Archfiend Eater of Nefariousness <- Not an activated effect to SS itself, so it works with witch

 

Basic End Board:

Possessed Partnerships + I:P

(Disclaimer: This deck requires you to have fair amount of APM, be warned! Try to get at least 10 materials attached to Plump or it might not be enough to win with 43 later on.)

Welcome! About a week ago or so, I have won with C9 thanks to Plump. This time, it will be with "Number 43". Let's roll!

 

 

Gameplan

1) At one point, discard one of Banishers with Dugares/Ravenous. After Link Summoning Saryuja, Special Summon first Banisher via its ability. Then, Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon to have "Primal Seed" loop ready.

2) Get rid of Saryuja with "Mystik Wok". Then, revive 3 x DARK monsters with "Monster Reborn" and adjust their levels to 2 with "Star Changer". Finally, overlay into "Number 43" with them.

3) Revive any monster and second Banisher with "Monster Reborn". Close the first Banisher with "Book of Moon" and adjust the levels of new monsters to 2 with "Star Changer".

4) With "Primal Seed" loop, fetch every spell from Banish Zone (BZ) to your hand if you can but at least 10 shall be sufficient except combo pieces.

5) When you have found all spells, here is your checklist as to which belongs where...

  • BZ: "Book of Moon" + "Mystik Wok" (If these aren't in BZ, use "Monster Reborn" and target both spells on revived target.)
  • Set: "Primal Seed" + "Book of Taiyou" + "Stoic Challenge" + "Time Thief Hack" + "Contract with the Void"

6) With monsters present in #3, XYZ Summon Plump. Afterwards, play "Contract with the Void" to send all spells you have from your hand to GY and start feeding your cat, which should include "Purrely Delicious Memory".

7) Open up Banisher from #3 with "Book of Taiyou" to start "Primal Seed" loop, again. Reason is that the ability of Plump isn't hard once per turn. So, you can reset Plump with Book spells and it can be well fed.

8) When there is nothing more to feed your cat, activate "Stoic Challenge" + "Time Thief Hack" on Plump. Alongside "Purrely Delicious Memory", Plump should have 600 + 300 + 300 = 1200 ATK per XYZ material.

9) Finally, activate "Mystik Wok" on Plump. Choose its ATK and let Number 43 convert healing into reflecting damage for massive FTK.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Stoic Challenge" can be found within "Blazing Warriors" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 540 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: The Branded Tri-brigade decklist that makes your opponent think you're "smoking sapphires"
deck_description:
Branded Tri brigade has always been an interesting deck to me, but it's felt like you'd end up foregoing one side of the deck over the other most of the time. I had always thought that the deckbuilds of Branded Tri has been in vain. however I had realized we do indeed have a solution, CRYSTAL BEAST.

With Crystal beasts being an archetype of Tri Beasts that pivot into a Dragon monster in hand, while also being a Rank 4 toobox. you can search both a Branded in High Spirits, as well as a Dragon monster to discard with it to make various fusion plays on your opponent's turn.

The main combo is Fraktall and any beast discard, and plays as follows:
Fraktall > Kitt > Nervall > Kerass To fill up grave after discarding the beast to summon Kerass is a typical play in any tri build.
however, instead of Banishing two to go into Ferijit or bearbrumm, you instead banish all 4 to make Shuraig, then make bearbrumm off the Kerass and Shuraig; who'll then add Crystal beast Sapphire pegasus.
You should then normal for it's effect to crystallize CB Rainbow dragon from deck, while leaving bearbrumm on field to dissuade nibiru until the tail end of the combo.
You then utilize Rainbow to add Rainbow or Rainbow dark and summon Pegasus from deck, then overlay your two Sapphires into Either Merrymaker or Force strix to continue comboing

There are a lot of branching paths with this deck that lead to a lot of variance with endboards, and a ton of things you can tech in. Try experimenting with different engines in the deck!

deck_description:
Hello and welcome to another guide, where I will be explaining how to burn your opponent down with "Cyber Summon Blaster". Let's get into action!

 

 

Gameplan

1) When you have exactly four cards in Main Deck and a Spellcaster monster in addition to four random ones present onboard, Link Summon Saryuja by using four random ones as materials. Don't use Spellcaster by accident.

2) Activate Saryuja and first shuffle 2 x Blaster cards, then anything but combo pieces. Therefore, whenever you activate "The Dark Magicians" (TDM), it will be guaranteed you can draw Blaster cards for sure.

3) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon "Black Luster Soldier" (BLS) with its ability to have "Primal Seed" loop active.

4) Special Summon "Fusion Parasite" with Saryuja, which lets you Fusion Summon TDM by using Parasite + Spellcaster as materials.

5) Activate first "Black Garden" and pass it to opponent with "Land Flipping". Then, activate second "Black Garden" and don't forget to draw first Blaster, which was set up in #2.

6) After playing "Clockwork Night", you can play "Acid Rain" but make sure you have "Monster Reborn" (MR) in your hand. Reason is that if you can't revive BLS with MR, you can't keep "Primal Seed" engine running. Then, revive TDM for another time with MR to draw second Blaster.

7) By reviving BLS and other monsters with MR, both Black Gardens will flourish your opponent's board with roses. Meanwhile, Blaster cards are going to burn your opponent to death. Just don't forget to reset everything with "Acid Rain" and always have "Monster Reborn" in-hand to keep going.

deck_description: Just a rank 8 theorycraft
Bystial Tearlament Heros (Jan 2024)
Test
Bystial Tearlament Heros (Jan 2024) V2
Just a silly deck idea.
Mannadium 2024 please let me know youre thoughts

Welcome! Here, "Number 43" takes the action with "Neo-Spacian Air Hummingbird" by giving your opponent lots of cards with "Gold Moon Coin" and "Magical Contract Door". So, where were we...

 

 

Gameplan

1) Send "Number 13" to GY, either by destroying it with "Ravenous" or using it as Link Material for "Saryuja".

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon "Chaos Emperor Dragon" with its ability to make "Primal Seed" loop active. As long as you don't banish "Number 13" by accident, you will be fine.

3) Special Summon Hummingbird, either with "Saryuja" or "Monster Reborn". Then, revive "Number 13" with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into "Number 43" with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch".

4) Give your opponent as many cards as possible with "Gold Moon Coin" and "Magical Contract Door". Know that in order to play Door, you have to reshuffle "Chaos Emperor Dragon" with "The Humble Sentry".

5) When you think it's enough, activate Hummingbird to gain LP. With Number 43 present, you can convert into damage. If it's not enough, you can reset Number 43 and Hummingbird with Book spells to try again.

6) Repeat #4 and/or #5 until opponent is dead.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Primal Seed" + "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "Magical Contract Door" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR and 60 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Book of Lunar Eclipse" can be found within "Beastly Claws of Terror" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 570 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Ib the World Chalice Justiciar Gaming
deck_description:
Looking back on Ham Prediction Princess, there are a lot of things that I would've liked to change for that Deck. The biggest change I would've made would be the inclusion of Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment in the Extra Deck. Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment is a Level 9 WATER Dragon Fusion Monster that requires 3 monsters with different names as material, but it can be made through contact fusion, banishing the materials you control. There are a number of Prediction Princess Decks that can make Fusion Trish, but Ham Prediction Princess is the Deck that I feel it belongs to the most. And it gets better with Ib now being unbanned and put to 1. Ib the World Chalice Justiciar searches for any World Chalice card on Synchro Summon which means that she can search for World Legacy Monstrosity, the cornerstone of every great and wacky Prediction Princess Deck. It doesn't take much effort to actually make Ib when you aren't trying to stick to a specific archetype. So in this Deck, we are using Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra, and Red Resonator to access Ib, Fusion Trish, and your whole Prediction Princess combo, ending on 3 different Flip Monsters. The 2.5 card combo in Ham Prediction Princess with Scorpio, Monstrosity, and a monster to discard is still a 2.5 card combo in this Deck, with you needing Scorpio, Red Resonator, and a monster to discard. Normal Summon Red Resonator. Red Resonator Special Summons a Level 4 or lower monster from hand on Normal Summon. Get yourself Scorpio from hand. Scorpio triggers on Special Summon to discard a monster to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. Special Summon Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck. Cobra triggers from being Special Summoned by a Predaplant monster's effect to search for Instant Fusion. Synchro Red Resonator and either Cobra or Scorpio into Ib. Ib searches for World Legacy Monstrosity on Synchro Summon. Activate Instant Fusion to Special Summon Master of Ham from Extra Deck. On Fusion Summon, Master of Ham Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck face-down. Get Whirlwind Weasel from Deck face-down. Banish Master of Ham, Ib, and Cobra/Scorpio (whichever is left) to Special Summon Fusion Trish from Extra Deck. Activate Monstrosity targeting Fusion Trish to get Deus-X Krawler and Prediction Princess Bibliomuse from Deck. Xyz Mardel and Fusion Trish into Mereologic Aggregator in your EMZ. Aggregator triggers on Xyz Summon to send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY. Herald triggers upon hitting the GY to search for Prediction Princess Tarotrei from Deck. Activate Aggregator’s other effect to target Herald in GY and detach Deus-X to attach that Herald in GY to it as material. Link off Aggregator for Gravity Controller who can only be Link Summoned using a monster in the EMZ except for a Link Monster. Herald is sent to the GY as a result of this which triggers its effect to add Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate Underworld Ritual of Prediction and tribute Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotrei from hand in face-up Attack Position. Bibliomuse triggers in GY as it was tributed and sent there to Special Summon itself back from GY in face-down Defense Position. Use Tarotrei’s effect to change it to face-up Attack Position which triggers Bibliomuse’s Flip Effect to add a Prediction Princess monster other than itself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand. Add Prediction Princess Tarotreith and another Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck to hand. Activate the Underworld Ritual you searched to once again Tribute Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith in face-down Defense Position. Proceed to your End Phase and Tarotrei can Special Summon Deus-X Krawler back from your GY in face-down Defense Position. Moving onto your opponent’s turn, in their Standby Phase, activate the Quick Effect of Tarotrei to change Tarotreith to face-up Attack Position. And now that Tarotreith is flipped face-up, its Flip Effect triggers to Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down. Special Summon Pot of the Forbidden from Deck face-down. On a new Chain, you can activate Tarotreith’s Quick Effect to flip your set Pot of the Forbidden, Deus-X Krawler, and Whirlwind Weasel to face-up Defense Position. Pot of the Forbidden’s Flip Effect triggers, allowing you to look at your opponent’s hand and a shuffle a card from it back into their Deck. Whirlwind Weasel’s Flip Effect triggers to lock your opponent out from activating Spell or Trap Cards for the rest of the turn. And Deus-X, while it doesn’t trigger, since it was flipped face-up, negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field while it is face-up. Is there anything different you could’ve done to produce a different result with what you had? Yes, but I will explain those things when I get to the individual cards. However, I think that this is definitely a big step up from what Ham Prediction Princess used to look like. Ib being able to search Monstrosity is just so good for Prediction Princess. Unlike Generaider, Monstrosity access is practically necessary for your Ritual searches through Herald and Aggregator as well as Bibliomuse access.

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. I think that this is all that you need for your Prediction Princess monsters. I may flip flop around the ratios of Tarotrei to Tarotreith depending on if the Deck I am playing needs to at least see a Ritual Monster for consistency reasons or if Tarotreith’s DARK Attribute is needed for Small World bridges, but this is the ratio I think works best. Tarotrei is your main enabler for your Flip Monsters and not Tarotreith because Tarotrei is the one flipping Tarotreith up in the first place which facilitates the rest of your Flips. Tarotrei has a Quick Effect that lets you target a monster on field and change it to face-up Attack Position if it is in face-down Defense or change it to face-down Defense Position if it is face-up on the field. And during your End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your hand or GY in face-down Defense Position. Tarotreith is a Ritual Flip Monster who must be either Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned from hand or GY by the effect of Prediction Princess Tarotrei during your End Phase. She has a Quick Effect that lets you choose between flipping any number of your face-down monsters to face-up Defense Position or flipping any number of your face-up monsters to face-down Defense Position. And her Flip Effect allows you to Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down. Ideally, you do not need to open either Tarotreith or Tarotrei because you should be able to get to both of them and the required Ritual Spells through Mereologic Aggregator and Herald of the Arc Light and the Flip Effect of Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. But drawing them does not hurt either because you can discard them for the effect of Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and then Ritual Summon them back from GY with Underworld Ritual of Prediction. It doesn’t help out against Bystials because they are LIGHT and DARK, but it’s definitely something that you can do. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY if she is Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect searches for a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck and while she is face-up on the field, she gives your Ritual Monsters targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. So, during your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can use an effect like Underworld Ritual of Prediction’s GY effect or Tarotreith’s effect to get this from Deck to give Tarotrei and Tarotreith targeting and destruction protection. Not only that, but you can trigger her Flip Effect again to search for a Prediction Princess monster and a Ritual Spell from Deck which can help you either go for lethal or help you rebuild your board on the following turn. So, instead of going for Pot of the Forbidden and filling up your last remaining Monster Zone with Pot, you can Summon Bibliomuse instead if you don’t value the draw 2 or hand rip. 2 Deus-X Krawler and 1 Pot of the Forbidden. Deus-X is a staple in all Prediction Princess Decks because it is literally the endboard for Prediction Princess. The whole reason for you even playing Prediction Princess is for this guy. After Deus-X is flipped face-up, it negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field while it remains in the Monster Zone. And if it is destroyed while on field field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck, which coincidentally gets you to either Tarotrei or Tarotreith in this Deck. Back before the DABL Prediction Princess support, I would activate Monstrosity targeting Tarotrei to get Pot of the Forbidden and Deus-X. I would then make True King of all Calamities (while it was still legal) with Tarotrei and Pot of the Forbidden and let Deus-X be popped during the End Phase via the effect of Monstrosity just to search for a Tarotrei for next turn. Pot of the Forbidden has a Flip Effect that allows you to choose an effect between drawing 2 cards (Pot of Greed), returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand (Giant Trunade), destroying all monsters your opponent controls (Raigeki), and looking at your opponent’s hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck (The Forceful Sentry). I am really back and forth on Pot of the Forbidden. For the most part, it is not necessary in a Prediction Princess Deck. You could play it for a different flavor of Flip Monster Effect, but it’s not necessary or really that good. The draw 2 is overshadowed by Bibliomuse searching a Prediction Princess and Ritual Spell. The Giant Trunade effect doesn’t really work in a world where Battle Traps aren’t around that much, or even at all. Sure it can help you get rid of floodgates and sure it can clear your opponent’s backrow if you flip Pot on your opponent’s turn after they set all of them, but you would be better off going blind into your opponent’s turn with Deus-X to negate activated monster effects. Destroying all monsters your opponent’s monsters is cool, but that’s if your opponent can make a board under Deus-X, Whirlwind Weasel, or even Guard Dog if you are playing it. And The Forceful Sentry effect is genuinely the best effect, but it means that you would have to make room for Pot for the Forbidden for a hand rip when your Deck easily fills up all 5 of your Monster Zones. 1 Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light which is a Level 9 which we can get off of the Lonefires we are playing and it searches a Plant or Generaider card on Normal or Special Summon. If anything, Mardel is a good Level 9 to target with Monstrosity and she can be Summoned off of Lonefire which is a bonus. Speaking of, 2 Lonefire Blossom which as a soft once per turn, can Tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. This gets you to your Predaplant stuff. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra. Scorpio on Normal or Special Summon sends a monster from hand to GY to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from Deck except itself. This gets you to Darlingtonia Cobra, who, if Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster, can add a Fusion or Polymerization Spell Card from your Deck to your hand once per Duel. This gets you to Instant Fusion for Master of Ham in this Deck, but I have a lot more Decks cooked up that share this Deck’s core that search other Fusion or Poly Spells. 3 Red Resonator. On Normal Summon, it can Special Summon a Level 4 or lower monster from your hand and on Special Summon, it can target a face-up monster on the field to gain LP equal to that monster’s ATK. Red Resonator is a Level 2 Tuner that can also get Scorpio onto the field to search for Instant Fusion via Cobra while also being able to Synchro a 2 and a 3 for Ib the World Chalice Justiciar to search for World Legacy Monstrosity. Could you play Assault Synchron? Yes, but even though it is technically a Level 2 Tuner that you can Special Summon for free from hand who has a Spell that can search for it (Tuning) like Resonator Call for Red Resonator, Assault Synchron is not the better choice than Red Resonator. For one, if you want to build this Deck in paper, Red Resonator is much cheaper. But more importantly, we can make better use of Red Resonator’s effects as opposed to the effects of Assault Synchron. Being locked out from anything other than Synchros from the Extra Deck while you have Assault Synchron Summoned by its own effect on the field doesn’t hurt, but when are you ever going to be using its effect when a Dragon Synchro Monster is Tributed or banished? Red Resonator’s effect to have you gain Life Points is much better in a tournament scene since you can Summon it back with a card like Cross-Sheep. And on the offchance that you accidentally mill Prediction Princess Bibliomuse or World Legacy Monstrosity off of Tuning, I would rather play Resonator Call. Last Main Deck Monster, we have is Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. The other piece of non-engine we are playing aside from Called By is Infinite Impermanence which you can replace for another Monster handtrap which can be used to up your monster count for Scorpio to discard.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Resonator Call. This just searches a Resonator monster from Deck and it is not once per turn which means that it can help with Deck-thinning as well. But more importantly, it gets you to Red Resonator which is essential to your combo. 1 Instant Fusion which gets you to Master of Ham who, in turn, gets you a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY in either face-up Attack Position or face-down Defense Position. And you can banish it from GY during either player’s Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from your Deck face-down. Being able to Ritual Summon from hand or GY is really useful if you need to send a monster from hand to GY for an effect, allowing you to send a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand to GY for that effect and still be able to Ritual Summon that monster from GY. Even if that is for you to Ritual Summon Tarotreith from GY since it can only be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned by Tarotrei’s effect even after it has been properly Ritual Summoned, this is still a good thing to have for the Deck since you can also use those Ritual Monsters as Ritual Fodder as well. Being able to get a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down means that you are able to put another Bibliomuse from your Deck face-down who can then be flipped face-up for searches for follow-up. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different original Type and Attribute than that monster you targeted but they must be different names. If anything, this card gets you Bibliomuse from Deck and sets you up to make Mereologic Aggregator to send Herald of the Arc Light. 1 World Legacy Succession which Special Summons a monster from your GY to a zone a Link Monster points to. If you do draw Monstrosity in your opening hand, you still have this card to search off of Ib. And then it can bring back something like a Level 9 monster to potentially help you go into a Rank 9 as a part of your endboard. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 1 Called By the Grave and 3 Infinite Impermanence.

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment. It is just a really easy Level 9 to Summon and you play it in your Extra Deck which means that it is available almost all of the time. 1 Master of Ham which you are getting off of Instant Fusion. If it is Fusion Summoned or flipped face-up, you can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your hand or Deck in face-down Defense. And if it is in your GY, you can banish 2 Flip Monsters from your GY and/or face-up field to Special Summon it back in face-down Defense. You aren’t really Special Summoning Master of Ham from GY with its effect that often, or even at all, but knowing that it is possible can be helpful. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which is a Level 5 Synchro Tuner monster and the only one of its effects that we are using is its effect on Synchro Summon which adds a World Legacy card from your Deck to your hand which gets you to World Legacy Monstrosity. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which we are sending from Extra Deck to GY with the effect of Mereologic Aggregator and if it is sent to GY, you can add a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck to hand. This effect is not once per turn, so if you are able to get Herald into the GY multiple times, you can get multiple searches. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer which is a Rank 9 that can detach any number of materials from itself to destroy an equal number of cards on the field and if it destroys a monster by battle it can attach the monster it destroys to itself as material. This is great for clearing the board and making Zeus. 1 Mereologic Aggregator who is a Rank 9 who send a monster from your Extra Deck to the GY on Xyz summon and it can also target any number of monsters in your GY up to the number of materials that it has and detach the same number of materials to reattach the targets in GY to it as Xyz Material. You can send Herald from Deck to GY with Aggregator for a search and reattach it and Link off Aggregator to send Herald to GY for another search. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity as a Rank 9 option for either interruption or for board clearing. 1 Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess and 1 Cross-Sheep. Just like my original Ham Prediction Princess Deck, you are able to make Apollousa if you want with your Predaplants and Instant Fusion through the usage of Cross-Sheep. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena as Link Monster options to go into. And 1 Gravity Controller who is a Link-1 that requires a monster in the EMZ except a Link Monster as Link Material which helps you to Link off Aggregator.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 2 Lightning Storm, 3 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.
SACRED BEAST 三玄魔 OCG 2024

deck_excerpt: Making Crystron Prediction Princess a reality (I guess...)
deck_description:
All of your Crystron non-Tuner monsters (aside from Crystron Sulfefnir) have their good effects that really define what the Deck’s main gimmick is locked behind a clause that prevents you from Special Summoning monsters from the Extra Deck except for Machine Synchro Monsters for the rest of the turn. Because of this, you can’t really make a Crystron Prediction Princess Deck. I got really close with a Scrap Crystron engine, but I wasn’t able to get there all the way. The biggest thing that I was lacking was a Tuner that floated into another Tuner. And that was when I realized there is a Tuner that floats into another Tuner: Denglong, First of the Yang Zing. Now, the issue was how would I be able to make both Ib the World Chalice Justiciar and Denglong and then transition to a Crystron Level 9 Synchro Monster (one that needs a Tuner Synchro + a non-Tuner Synchro or another that needs 2 Tuners + 1 non-Tuner). Then it came to me: Red Resonator, Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra, Predaplant Ambulomelides, and Ultra Polymerization. Just the same starters as Ib Ham Prediction Princess, but searching for Ultra Poly rather than Instant Fusion and going into both Ib and Denglong. Crystron has 2 Level 9 monsters and we are looking at both of them today. First off, we have Crystron Phoenix which is a Level 9 WATER Machine Accel Synchro Monster which means that it needs a Tuner Synchro Monster + 1 or more non-Tuner Synchro Monsters as material. On Synchro Summon, you can banish all Spell/Trap Cards your opponent controls and in their GY. And if it is Synchro Summoned and destroyed by battle or card effect, you can target another monster in your GY and Special Summon it. The second is Crystron Quariongandrax which is a Level 9 WATER Machine Double Tuning Synchro Monster and it needs 2 or more Tuner monsters + 1 non-Tuner monster as material. On Synchro Summon, you can target monsters your opponent controls and/or in their GY up to the number of Synchro Materials used for the Synchro Summon of this card and banish them. And if it is Synchro Summoned and destroyed by battle or card effect, you can target a banished monster except itself and Special Summon it to your field. Just to make note, we are not using their effects and we are only using them as Level 9 targets for Monstrosity on field. Again, it is the same 2.5 card combo that you use for Ib Ham Prediction Princess, but you go through a different line in order to get to Phoenix or Quariongandrax. Red Resonator, Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, and a monster to discard. Normal Summon Red Resonator and use its effect to Special Summon Scorpio from hand. Scorpio triggers to discard a monster and Special Summon Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck. Cobra adds Ultra Polymerization from Deck to hand. Pay 2000 LP to fuse Cobra and Scorpio together with Ultra Poly to make Predaplant Ambulomelides. Ambulo adds Predapruning from Deck on Fusion Summon. Banish Ultra Poly from GY to target Ambulo on field to Special Summon both Cobra and Scorpio from GY. Synchro Red Resonator and Scorpio into Denglong, First of the Yang Zing. Activate Denglong’s effect to send Chiwen, Light of the Yang Zing from Deck to GY to make Denglong a Level 1 monster. Activate Ambulo’s effect to Tribute itself to Special Summon a Predaplant Moray Nepenthes from Deck. Synchro Level 1 Denglong and Level 4 Nepenthes into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar and use its effect to add World Legacy Monstrosity from Deck to hand. Denglong floats into another Chiwen from Deck when sent to GY. Now, you can make 2 different decisions. You can Synchro Chiwen and Cobra you have left on field into Herald of the Arc Light and then Synchro Ib and Herald into Crystron Phoenix or you can not make Herald and Synchro Ib, Chiwen, and Cobra into Crystron Quariongandrax. And since you already searched Monstrosity with Ib in your combo, you now have full Prediction Princess combo. It’s a shame that I wasn’t able to make this possible with mainly Crystron cards, but just getting these two pains out of the pool of Level 9 monsters I have left to experiment with is definitely nice.

For the Main Deck monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and during your End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from the GY face-down if she is Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it. 1 Predaplant Moray Nepenthes. This is just a Level 4 Predaplant we can grab off of Predaplant Ambulomelides. You could even play Predaplant Spinodionaea if you wanted. You could even just not play this card. The reason why we are even playing this in the first place is to have Denglong, First of the Yang Zing module its Level to 1 by sending a Chiwen, Light of the Yang Zing from Deck to GY so that you can Tune the Level 1 Denglong with your Level 4 Predaplant (off of Ambulo) to make Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. You could just not play the Level 4 Predaplant and opt to Special Summon a copy of Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio that you have left in Deck. And you could have Denglong send a Jiaotu, Darkness of the Yang Zing to the GY instead to make it a Level 2. Then you could Tune Level 2 Denglong with Level 3 Scorpio to make Ib. It’s based on preference, so you could be playing the Level 4 Predaplant or not. 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra which adds a Polymerization or Fusion Spell Card from Deck to hand if it is Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster once per Duel. We are using this to get Ultra Polymerization for our Phoenix/Quariongandrax line, but we are playing Instant Fusion and Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment if you want to go down that line instead. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio which sends a monster from hand to GY on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from Deck. 3 Lonefire Blossom which can tribute a Plant to Special Summon a Plant from Deck. 3 Red Resonator which can Special Summon a Level 4 or lower monster from hand on Normal Summon or can target a face-up monster on field and have you gain Life Points equal to that monster’s ATK on Special Summon. 1 Jiaotu, Darkness of the Yang Zing as a Level 2 Yang Zing to send off of Denglong for reasons explained earlier. 2 Chiwen, Light of the Yang Zing as a Level 1 Yang Zing for Denglong to send and to also float into. And finally, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring which can be used as a handtrap or an additional monster in your Deck to pitch for Scorpio’s effect.

For Spell/Traps: 3 Pot of Prosperity. 1 Predapruning which is an Equip Spell that Special Summons a Predaplant from GY and equips it with this card. And when this card leaves the field, that monster is destroyed. You don’t need to play this card, but you could use it as a way to get more Link Material onto field after searching it off of Predaplant Ambulomelides. 1 Ultra Polymerization which pays 2000 LP to Fusion Summon using 2 monsters you control where neither player can activate cards or effects in response to its activation. And you can banish it from GY to target a monster Special Summoned by Ultra Poly to Special Summon the Fusion Materials used for its Summon from GY. 1 Instant Fusion. 3 Resonator Call to search for Red Resonator. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can also banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 World Legacy Succession which Special Summons a monster from GY to a zone a Link Monster points to. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 from hand or target a Level 9 you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than that monster but with different names. 

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment which can be Special Summoned by banishing 3 monsters with different names you control and is a Level 9 itself. 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides which needs 2 Predaplants as Fusion Material, it adds a Predap card from Deck to hand on Fusion Summon, and it can Tribute a monster you control or an opponent’s monster with a Predator Counter to Special Summon a Predaplant from Deck. 1 Crystron Phoenix and 1 Crystron Quariongandrax. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which is a Synchro Tuner that adds a World Legacy card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon. 1 Denglong, First of the Yang Zing which is another Synchro Tuner that adds a Yang Zing card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon, can send a Wyrm from Deck to GY to change its Level to the Level of the sent monster, and can float into a Yang Zing monster from Deck if sent to GY. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which can search for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to GY. 1 Mereologic Aggregator, 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows, and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 2 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 1 Kurikara Divincarnate, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 3 Evenly Matched.

Monster Tech

Dimensional Alchemist can most notably recover a monster from the banished zone when he is destroyed on your side of the field and sent to the graveyard. Doomcaliber Knight has powerful stats and a monster negation effect that's great for aggressive plays, but be careful because he can negate your own monster effect too. Marshmallon is a defensive monster that can't be destroyed by battle and can punish an opponent with a hefty 1000 burn damage if it is face-down when attacked. You can take control of an opponent's monster with Brain Control or Mind Control, then banish it with Cyber Valley to draw 2 cards.

deck_excerpt: Let's LINK INTO THE VRAINS straight to Masters 1 with Cyberse Mathmech!
deck_description:
I've pulled a critical amount of Mathmech cards from selection pack, Mighty Contenders so I thought now is the time for me to create a guide about our favourite digital combo deck! Due to the recent release of the "Firewall" support and Masterduel's very lenient attitude towards Cyberse last banlist (only brought Diameter to 1 rather than Circular), I feel that Cyberse Mathmech is well positioned to be a ladder deck of choice for 2024!

Over the years, the Cyberse type in Yu-Gi-Oh has amassed support for various in-theme archetypes, most notably Mathmech, Code Talker and Firewall. Now in 2024, all the strongest Cyberse archetypes can come together to create an powerful amalgamation similar to Dragonlink and Plantlink - Cyberse Mathmech!

From 1-2 cards, this strategy ends on a ridiculously insane amount of interruptions, resources and follow-up while packing lots of extra space for staples. Yusaku (aka Playmaker's) deck from VRAINS definitely has reached it's peak potential - and now it's all available in Masterduel so you can climb to the very top of ladder!
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
Cyberse Mathmech is a monstrous pile of synergistic Cyberse cards and their associated support.
 
The biggest archetype present is MATHMECH, composed of 11 cards. The centerpiece of the Mathmech cards is the unbelievably strong Mathmech Circular, which represents full combo for this deck just by itself. Addition, Subtraction and Equation are all extenders so the pilot can make a stronger than usual board, or to play through interruption. Finally, Multiplication is a target to be sent from deck to GY by Firewall Dragon Terahertz, bringing the boss monster to 11000 ATK!
 
Generic CYBERSE SUPPORT cards number 9 cards. The Firewall package involves 4 cards - Firewall Defenser as the normal summon and Firewall Guardian as the target to summon from deck. They constantly summon more link material to the field so that the duelist can link climb during their plays. x3 Parallel Exceed is included since it makes an easy rank 4 as long as you have a link zone on field, which is typically Alembertian so it can search Circular and you can full combo from there. x2 Cynet Mining is included to search any Cyberse monster.
 
Since the strategy is extremely consistent, a large portion of the deck is composed of STAPLE cards. First, the mandatory "Maxx C" package is included to counter the ever dominant card of Masterduel's meta - there exists 8 cards that counter the insect, that being x3 Ash Blossom, x2 Called By, x1 Crossout, and x2 Psy-Frame Gear Gamma. x3 Small World is included since it searches every card in the deck! This card can search Mathmech Circulr so you can full combo, or even Ash Blossom so you can insulate your plays vs. an opponent's Maxx "C."
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Cyberse Mathmech functions as a combo deck that fields 2-3 negates, draw 2, multiple non-targeting removals, and a handloop for 1 card while allowed to fully combo going first. This deck features many one card starters, and ways to search your 1-card starter (2 level 4s -> Alembertian -> Mathmech Circular). Even if this deck is interrupted, this strategy has so many extenders that it can shrug off weaker handtraps with ease. Cyberse Mathmech can also OTK on a dime with an Accesscode Talker that can attack twice (totalling 8600ATK!) with as little as one card if allowed to fully combo!
 
The main combo of Cyberse Mathmech revolve around it's key card - Mathmech Circular (think about this card as this deck's "Branded Fusion" or "Sky Striker Mobilize - Engage"). 1 circular leads to 3 omni-negates, multiple removals, 1 handloop and follow-up/GY set-up for next turn!
 
Mathmech Circular = Set Mathmech Superfactorial (Summons Laplacian which is non-targeting removal of monster, S/T, and handloops 1 card + 1 omni-negate if made with Diameter), 8000ATK Firewall Dragon Darkfluid Terahertz (2 omni-negates by sending Desavewurm and Mereologic Aggregator to GY) + follow-up.
  1. Activate Circular's effect in hand to summon itself by sending to GY Sigma.
  2. Summon Sigma's effect in GY to summon itself.
  3. Activate Circular's trigger effect to search for Superfactorial from deck. If you already have it, search for Equation instead. 
  4. XYZ summon Alembertian using Circular + Sigma. Activate Alembertian's on-summon effect to search for Diameter from deck. 
  5. Normal summon Diameter to summon Circular from GY. 
  6. Link summon Link Decoder using Diameter. 
  7. Link summon Splash Mage using Circular + Alembertian. 
  8. Summon from the GY Circular with Splash mage's effect. 
  9. Link summon Transcode Talker using Splash Mage + Link Decoder. (Be sure to keep Transcode's link zone empty).
  10. Activate Link Decoder's effect to summon itself from the GY. 
  11. Summon from the GY Splash Mage to a zone Transcode points to. 
  12. Link summon G Golem Crystal Heart using Transcode + Link Decoder. (Be sure to keep Crystal Heart's link zone empty).
  13. Summon from the GY Transcode to a zone Crystal Heart points to. 
  14. Link summon Firewall Dragon Terahertz using Splash Mage + Crystal Heart + Circular so that it is co-linked to Transcode. 
  15. Activate Terahertz's effect to send Cyberse Desavewurm from Extra Deck to GY. 
  16. During your opponent's turn activate Superfactorial for field removals, handrip and an omni-negate for Laplacian. During your opponent's turn, send from Extra Deck to GY Mereologic Aggregator to negate a face-up card your opponent controls. 
With proper extenders, this strategy can also summon Heatsoul for a draw 2. If you feel like you've been interrupted too much or you hand isn't optimal, you can end off on Heatsoul, or Heatsoul + Transcode, depending on your situation. Opponents typically prevent you from turning on the "Mathmech" part of the interruption online like stopping you from searching Superfactorial or preventing/banishing Mathmech monsters in the GY. In those scenarios, variations of the Heatsoul, Transcode and Terahertz set-up are still very good. 
 
Going second Cyberse Mathmech, attempts to handtrap the opponent to simplify their game state. 
 
The amount of momentum that Circular and any extenders that the strategy gives the duelist should allow them to create Accesscode with 3-4 pops coupled with Update Jammer's double attack. 
 
Alternatively, Terahertz can be created and summoned to the Extra Monster Zone. Terahertz can send to GY Mathmech Multiplication to give it WHOPPING 11000ATK and OTK even through a 3000ATK monster! 
 
Even if the Cyberse Mathmech pilot cannot OTK opponent, the gamestate should be simplified enough to finish the opponent next turn. The extra link material on board can also be used to make Heatsoul so that you can draw additional resources to further handtrap your opponent and for extra follow-up next turn. 
 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Keep in mind that activating Circular's effect only allows 1 monster to attack for the rest of the turn. Make sure the monster you attack with (Either Accesscode/Terahertz) can finish the job!
  • It is best to OTK with Terahertz when your opponent has a attack position monster on the field with 3000 or less attack and nothing else to interrupt you (for example, backrow). Accesscode is best used to OTK 
  • Be mindful of the link zones when you summon monsters like Transcode and Crystal Heart. They need those zones empty to use their effects! Also, certain monsters enjoy being co-linked with Transcode for additional protection from targeting effects - keep this in mind when building your board!
  • If you get Maxx "C"'d and you have no cards to counter it, you either end your turn or you finish off your opponent immediately. It's not worth it giving your opponent 15+ cards if you combo!
  • If you feel that your opponent is holding an interruption in their hand like Nibiru or impermanence to interrupt you, summon Alembertian with Diameter so you have an omni-negate to insulate your combolines. 
  • While Desavewurm can omni-negate immediately, Mereologic Aggregator only negates AFTER it was sent to the GY a face-up card already on the field. Aggregator is best used negating crucial face up cards with spell speed 1 effects like Kashtira Birth, Branded Lost or Dragon's Ravine. 
  • Believe it or not, any normal summonable handtrap (Like Ash or Effect Veiler) + Parallel Exceed is full combo. Normal your handtrap -> Link away to Almiraj -> Parallel Exceed summons itself from hand + another from deck -> XYZ summon Alembertian -> Search Mathmech Circular -> full Cyberse combo! Even your handtraps are starters!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Mathmech Circular is one of the most insane cards ever printed. A 1 card enabler for an entire Yugioh monster type that finishes on a several interruptions, omninegates, removals and resources is crazy - and right now it's still at 3 in Masterduel! Adding on top generic Cyberse support to enable the strategy even further with extenders and consistency makes the deck even more potent, leaving it capable of plowing through established boards with engine alone. The incredible power and hyper consistency of Cyberse Mathmech makes the deck one of my favourite powerhouses to abuse on ladder since it's reliable, consistent, powerful and nigh unstoppable!
 
Let's LINK INTO THE VRAINS straight to Masters 1 with Cyberse Mathmech!

deck_excerpt: Number 43 FTK ft. Healing Wave Generator
deck_description:
Hello there, feeling energetic? If not, don't worry, "Healing Wave Generator" is here to energize you while "Number 43" does the same for the opponent. It will be shocking for them.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Throughout the game, discard Coltwing+Generator with Ravenous and send Number 13 to GY.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to setup your Primal Seed loop. As long as you don't banish Number 13 and/or Generator with Chaos Emperor by accident, all is well.

3) Revive Number 13 with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into Number 43 with "Rank-Up-Magic Launch". Place Number 43 on Extra Monster Zone (EMZ). Then, revive Coltwing with "Monster Reborn" and replace it with a token by playing "Vertical Landing". By reviving Coltwing another time with "Monster Reborn", it should generate two more tokens.

4) The current level of Coltwing is based on the sum of level of tokens and original level of Coltwing. This is addition, which is actually done only by tokens, not setting its level to fixed amount. Therefore, by playing "Galaxy Queen's Light" on Coltwing, its level will increase with respect to level of tokens. Reason is that you will also increase the level of tokens. Here is the process:

  • At first, the level of Coltwing will be level 13 >>> Coltwing (4) + Token (3) + Token (3) + Token (3)
  • Galaxy Queen's Light >>> Target Coltwing (level 13) >>> Tokens will be level 13
  • New calculation = Token (13) + Token (13) + Token (13) + Coltwing (4) = Coltwing (43)

5) Repeat the step explained in #4, by targeting only on Coltwing and nothing else.

6) When you think it's enough or you couldn't play "Galaxy Queen's Light" due to limits, get rid of a token with "Offerings to the Doomed" and revive Generator with "Monster Reborn".

7) Activate Generator and choose Chaos Emperor. Since Chaos Emperor has very high level value, you will gain a lot of LP, with multiples of 100 per level in mind. Thanks to Number 43, you can convert the LP you have gained into damage and direct it to your opponent for the FTK.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Primal Seed" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

deck_excerpt: Everliving Underworld Cannon FTK ft. Zombie World + Poseidra
deck_description:
So, it's known that "Giant Trunade" is banned, seen in "Side Deck". What if I told you that you can legally play it but named as "Poseidra, the Atlantean Dragon"? Thanks to Attribute/Type changers, namely "Maple Maiden" and "Zombie World", you can still do that. Let me show you.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Link Summon Saryuja. Then, Special Summon Panda/Monk, if you choose Panda as material for Saryuja by accident.

2) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Chaos Emperor Dragon with its ability to make sure "Primal Seed" loop is ready.

3) Clear Extra Monster Zone (EMZ) and 3 x Main Monster Zones (MMZ) with "Offerings to the Doomed". Don't destroy Panda/Chaos by accident.

4) Play "Tri-Wight" to revive 3 x Level 1 dudes, one of which has to be Tuner. Then, Synchro Summon Maple with Panda + 3 x Level 1 dudes and place Maple on EMZ. Choose WATER as Attribute.

5) Place "Zombie World" and 3 x "Everliving Underworld Cannon" (EUC) cards. Then, play "Tri-Wight" for another time. Doesn't matter which monsters you are going to bring forth.

6) 3 x EUC cards have dealt 3 x 800 = 2400 damage in total. To repeat this step, you can Special Summon Poseidra by tributing three little dudes. Thus, all Spells and Traps will be returned to hand and EUC were reset. You can destroy Poseidra with Offerings because its ability can also trigger even in GY and it's not hard once per turn, fortunately.

7) Repeat what was explained in #5 alongside placing ME-PSY-YA to unlock "Primal Seed" loop and #6 until opponent is dead.

deck_description:
A Deck created by ChatGPT using the prompt "Create a Fur Hire deck with a short description of how the deck is played in Yu-Gi-Oh!"

Please bear in mind that as useful ChatGPT is it is by far not perfect. There will be inconsistencies and problems with deck building. Most of the time it will create a deck either under 40 cards or randomly have extra deck cards in the main deck. I've done some fine tuning whilst trying to not impact too much what ChatGPT has made.

A short description made by ChatGPT about how the deck functions.

Deck Strategy:

Fur Hire Monsters: The main strategy is to swarm the field with Fur Hire monsters. Each Fur Hire monster has effects that trigger when Special Summoned, allowing you to gain advantage and control the field.

Mayhem Fur Hire: This Continuous Spell is a key card for the deck. It enables additional Special Summons of Fur Hire monsters during your Main Phase.

Fur Hire Behemoth: This Continuous Trap provides protection for your Fur Hire monsters by preventing them from being targeted or destroyed by card effects.

Infinite Impermanence: This hand trap is versatile and can disrupt your opponent's plays by negating the effects of a face-up monster.

Extra Deck: Rafale, Champion Fur Hire is your boss monster. It can negate the effects of all face-up monsters your opponent controls. The Sky Striker Ace monsters provide additional Link options.

Consistency Cards: Pot of Desires and Upstart Goblin help you draw into your key cards faster. Called by the Grave is useful for protecting your combo pieces from hand traps.

Gameplan

1) Discard Gale with Ravenous. After Link Summoning Saryuja, place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon Black Luster Soldier (BLS) with its ability to make "Primal Seed" loop active. Banish Saryuja with BLS but don't banish Formula by accident.

2) With Swirl + Slime in-hand, Fusion Summon Oracle by using both as materials in-hand via Slime. Then, place Oracle on Extra Monster Zone (EMZ).

3) Place "Lair of Darkness" to change Attribute of all monsters into DARK. Then, revive Formula + Swirl + Slime with "Monster Reborn" and overlay into Number 43.

4) After reviving Gale with "Monster Reborn", place "Brain Research Lab" and play "Temple >>> Surgery" combo to change Type of all monsters into Psychic. From here on, you can use the ability of Gale as many times as possible while triggering Research Lab, which can be done with "Pot of Avarice" and "Pot of Generosity" combinations.

5) Repeat what was explained in #4 until you think it's enough. Then, revive Baronne and destroy Research Lab. Here is what is going to happen...

deck_excerpt: A statistically optimized Tearlaments build for the Jan 1st 2024 meta.
deck_description:
Main Deck: 

The main deck is designed to optimize opening hands and mills. Most opening hands will have 2-3 lines of play going first.

1 Line of play probability: 99.06%

2 Lines of play probability: 90.7%

3 Lines of play probability: 64.59%

Going second You'll open 3 lines of play 80.28% of the time allowing you to play through boards with ease. 

 

For mill probability optimization you have the following (these stats go up dramatically if you search out planet or kings sarc prior to milling, or if you open the cards that do not have mill effects):

hitting 1 effect off of milling 3: 90.19%

hitting 2 effects off of milling 3: 53.85% 

hitting 2 effects off of milling 6: 92.93%

hitting 3 effects off of milling 6: 71.73%

For going first your goal is to set up a rulkallos, grapha or toad prior to your 5th summon, then go for a zombie vampire play to set up mills, and then focus on creating a hand and board with lots of interaction (sulliek/metanoise on board, tear kash in hand (or toad on board with tear kash in grave), hapi on board if possible). Try to keep all 3 tear names in your deck to extend further on the opponents turn. Creating a winda on the opponents turn can be devastating. Depending on the opponents deck making abyss dweller turn 1 can be an incredibly potent move. 

For going second, side out winda for guardian chimera and grapha for TY-PHON. Droplet and super poly can be used over cards that are better going first (night sword serpent, terraforming (weak to droll), trivikarma (weak to droll), wraitsoth (weak to droll))to improve specific matchups. Side both against cintureon, super poly against most fire decks, and super poly against most fusion decks aswell. You can also use heartbeat for field/continuous spell dependant decks, and cryme for going first or against decks with lots of bystials. Gamaciel can be used to beat out decks where super poly is not as potent. Gamaciel could even be replaced with lava golem or sphere mode as the normal summon is not always relevant in this deck. Gamaciel could even be replaced with something like chaos hunter or imperial iron wall, to soften the hardest matchups which are typically kashtira and bystial heavy decks. Floo and vanquish soul seem like hard matchups on paper but you can out-gas them fairly easily just by having 2-3 lines of play. If you get shifter'd and they are going first youre typically okay as you can play on their turn using scream, traps, and quick effects. If you're going first do whatever you can to survive to your second turn and maintain a line of play.
